119 BOOLEAN
120 CcPinFileData (
121  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
122  IN PLARGE_INTEGER FileOffset,
123  IN ULONG Length,
124  IN BOOLEAN ReadOnly,
125  IN BOOLEAN WriteOnly,
126  IN ULONG Flags,
127  OUT PBCB *Bcb,
128  OUT PVOID *BaseAddress,
129  OUT PLARGE_INTEGER BeyondLastByte
130  )
131 
132 /*++
133 
134 Routine Description:
135 
136  This routine locks the specified range of file data into memory.
137 
138  Note that the data desired by the caller (or the first part of it)
139  may be in one of three states:
140 
141  No Bcb exists which describes the data
142 
143  A Bcb exists describing the data, but it is not mapped
144  (BcbOut->BaseAddress == NULL)
145 
146  A Bcb exists describing the data, and it is mapped
147 
148  Given the above three states, and given that the caller may call
149  with either Wait == FALSE or Wait == TRUE, this routine has basically
150  six cases. What has to be done, and the order in which things must be
151  done varies quite a bit with each of these six cases. The most
152  straight-forward implementation of this routine, with the least amount
153  of branching, is achieved by determining which of the six cases applies,
154  and dispatching fairly directly to that case. The handling of the
155  cases is summarized in the following table:
156 
157  Wait == TRUE Wait == FALSE
158  ------------ -------------
159 
160  no Bcb Case 1: Case 2:
161 
162  CcAllocateInitializeBcb CcMapAndRead (exit if FALSE)
163  Acquire Bcb Exclusive CcAllocateInitializeBcb
164  Release BcbList SpinLock Acquire Bcb Shared if not ReadOnly
165  CcMapAndRead w/ Wait Release BcbList SpinLock
166  Convert/Release Bcb Resource
167 
168  Bcb not Case 3: Case 4:
169  mapped
170  Increment PinCount Acquire Bcb Exclusive (exit if FALSE)
171  Release BcbList SpinLock CcMapAndRead (exit if FALSE)
172  Acquire Bcb Excl. w/ Wait Increment PinCount
173  if still not mapped Convert/Release Bcb Resource
174  CcMapAndRead w/ Wait Release BcbList SpinLock
175  Convert/Release Bcb Resource
176 
177  Bcb mapped Case 5: Case 6:
178 
179  Increment PinCount if not ReadOnly
180  Release BcbList SpinLock Acquire Bcb shared (exit if FALSE)
181  if not ReadOnly Increment PinCount
182  Acquire Bcb Shared Release BcbList SpinLock
183 
184  It is important to note that most changes to this routine will affect
185  multiple cases from above.
186 
187 Arguments:
188 
189  FileObject - Pointer to File Object for file
190 
191  FileOffset - Offset in file at which map should begin
192 
193  Length - Length of desired map in bytes
194 
195  ReadOnly - Supplies TRUE if caller will only read the mapped data (i.e.,
196  TRUE for CcCopyRead, CcMapData and CcMdlRead and FALSE for
197  everyone else)
198 
199  WriteOnly - The specified range of bytes will only be written.
200 
201  Flags - (PIN_WAIT, PIN_EXCLUSIVE, PIN_NO_READ, etc. as defined in cache.h)
202 
203  Bcb - Returns a pointer to the Bcb representing the pinned data.
204 
205  BaseAddress - Returns base address of desired data
206 
207  BeyondLastByte - Returns the File Offset of the first byte beyond the
208  last accessible byte.
209 
210 Return Value:
211 
212  FALSE - if PIN_WAIT was set, and it was impossible to lock all
213  of the data without blocking
214  TRUE - if the desired data, is being returned
215 
216 Raises:
217 
218  STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES - If a pool allocation failure occurs.
219  This can only occur if Wait was specified as TRUE. (If Wait is
220  specified as FALSE, and an allocation failure occurs, this
221  routine simply returns FALSE.)
222 
223 --*/
224 
225 {
226  PSHARED_CACHE_MAP SharedCacheMap;
227  LARGE_INTEGER TrialBound;
228  KLOCK_QUEUE_HANDLE LockHandle;
229  PBCB BcbOut = NULL;
230  ULONG ZeroFlags = 0;
231  LOGICAL SpinLockAcquired = FALSE;
232  BOOLEAN Result = FALSE;
233 
234  ULONG ReceivedLength;
235  ULONG ActivePage;
236  ULONG PageIsDirty;
237  PVACB Vacb = NULL;
238 
239  DebugTrace(+1, me, "CcPinFileData:\n", 0 );
240  DebugTrace( 0, me, " FileObject = %08lx\n", FileObject );
241  DebugTrace2(0, me, " FileOffset = %08lx, %08lx\n", FileOffset->LowPart,
242  FileOffset->HighPart );
243  DebugTrace( 0, me, " Length = %08lx\n", Length );
244  DebugTrace( 0, me, " Flags = %02lx\n", Flags );
245 
246  //
247  // Get pointer to SharedCacheMap via File Object.
248  //
249 
250  SharedCacheMap = FileObject->SectionObjectPointer->SharedCacheMap;
251 
252  //
253  // See if we have an active Vacb, that we need to free.
254  //
255 
256  GetActiveVacb( SharedCacheMap, OldIrql, Vacb, ActivePage, PageIsDirty );
257 
258  //
259  // If there is an end of a page to be zeroed, then free that page now,
260  // so it does not cause our data to get zeroed. If there is an active
261  // page, free it so we have the correct ValidDataGoal.
262  //
263 
264  if ((Vacb != NULL) || (SharedCacheMap->NeedToZero != NULL)) {
265 
266  CcFreeActiveVacb( SharedCacheMap, Vacb, ActivePage, PageIsDirty );
267  Vacb = NULL;
268  }
269 
270  //
271  // Make sure the calling file system is not asking to map beyond the
272  // end of the section, for example, that it did not forget to do
273  // CcExtendCacheSection.
274  //
275 
276  ASSERT( ( FileOffset->QuadPart + (LONGLONG)Length ) <=
277  SharedCacheMap->SectionSize.QuadPart );
278 
279  //
280  // Initially clear output
281  //
282 
283  *Bcb = NULL;
284  *BaseAddress = NULL;
285 
286  if (!FlagOn(Flags, PIN_NO_READ)) {
287 
288  *BaseAddress = CcGetVirtualAddress( SharedCacheMap,
289  *FileOffset,
290  &Vacb,
291  &ReceivedLength );
292 
293  } else {
294 
295  //
296  // In the PIN_NO_READ case, we simply need to make sure that the
297  // sparse structure containing the Bcb listheads is expanded in the
298  // region of the file we are interested in.
299  //
300  // Fake a ReceivedLength that matches the remaining bytes in the view.
301  //
302 
303  ReceivedLength = VACB_MAPPING_GRANULARITY -
304  (ULONG)(FileOffset->QuadPart & (VACB_MAPPING_GRANULARITY - 1));
305 
306  //
307  // Now simply cause a reference that will expand a multilevel Vacb.
308  //
309 
310  CcReferenceFileOffset( SharedCacheMap, *FileOffset );
311  }
312 
313  //
314  // Acquire Bcb List Exclusive to look for Bcb
315  //
316 
317  KeAcquireInStackQueuedSpinLock( &SharedCacheMap->BcbSpinLock, &LockHandle );
318  SpinLockAcquired = TRUE;
319 
320  //
321  // Use try to guarantee cleanup on the way out.
322  //
323 
324  try {
325 
326  LOGICAL Found;
327  LARGE_INTEGER FOffset;
328  LARGE_INTEGER TLength;
329 
330  //
331  // Search for Bcb describing the largest matching "prefix" byte range,
332  // or where to insert it.
333  //
334 
335  TrialBound.QuadPart = FileOffset->QuadPart + (LONGLONG)Length;
336  Found = CcFindBcb( SharedCacheMap, FileOffset, &TrialBound, &BcbOut );
337 
338 
339  //
340  // Cases 1 and 2 - Bcb was not found.
341  //
342  // First calculate data to pin down.
343  //
344 
345  if (!Found) {
346 
347  //
348  // Get out if the user specified PIN_IF_BCB.
349  //
350 
351  if (FlagOn(Flags, PIN_IF_BCB)) {
352 
353  //
354  // We need to zap BcbOut since this is a hint to the cleanup code
355  // to remove the Bcb if we are returning FALSE.
356  //
357 
358  BcbOut = NULL;
359  try_return( Result = FALSE );
360  }
361 
362  //
363  // Not found, calculate data to pin down.
364  //
365  // Round local copy of FileOffset down to page boundary, and
366  // round copies of size and minimum size up. Also make sure that
367  // we keep the length from crossing the end of the SharedCacheMap.
368  //
369 
370  FOffset = *FileOffset;
371  TLength.QuadPart = TrialBound.QuadPart - FOffset.QuadPart;
372 
373  TLength.LowPart += FOffset.LowPart & (PAGE_SIZE - 1);
374  ReceivedLength += FOffset.LowPart & (PAGE_SIZE - 1);
375 
376  //
377  // At this point we can calculate the ReadOnly flag for
378  // the purposes of whether to use the Bcb resource, and
379  // we can calculate the ZeroFlags.
380  //
381 
382  if ((!ReadOnly && !FlagOn(SharedCacheMap->Flags, PIN_ACCESS)) || WriteOnly) {
383 
384  //
385  // We can always zero middle pages, if any.
386  //
387 
388  ZeroFlags = ZERO_MIDDLE_PAGES;
389 
390  if (((FOffset.LowPart & (PAGE_SIZE - 1)) == 0) &&
391  (Length >= PAGE_SIZE)) {
392  ZeroFlags |= ZERO_FIRST_PAGE;
393  }
394 
395  if ((TLength.LowPart & (PAGE_SIZE - 1)) == 0) {
396  ZeroFlags |= ZERO_LAST_PAGE;
397  }
398  }
399 
400  //
401  // We treat Bcbs as ReadOnly (do not acquire resource) if they
402  // are in sections for which we have not disabled modified writing.
403  //
404 
405  if (!FlagOn(SharedCacheMap->Flags, MODIFIED_WRITE_DISABLED)) {
406  ReadOnly = TRUE;
407  }
408 
409  TLength.LowPart = (ULONG) ROUND_TO_PAGES( TLength.LowPart );
410 
411  //
412  // Round BaseAddress and FOffset down to the bottom of a page.
413  //
414 
415  *BaseAddress = ((PCHAR)*BaseAddress - (FileOffset->LowPart & (PAGE_SIZE - 1)));
416  FOffset.LowPart &= ~(PAGE_SIZE - 1);
417 
418  //
419  // We cannot use a zero page optimization beyond VDL because we
420  // cannot be guaranteed that the caller will track this page as
421  // being dirty. If the zero-page optimization is used, the page
422  // returned by Mm will be marked dirty (MmCheckCachedPageState).
423  // If Cc does not properly track this page as being dirty, the
424  // dirty page may never be written since. There are cases when
425  // the file system will not allow the modified page writer to
426  // write out dirty pages beyond VDL (e.g., NTFS for compressed
427  // files).
428  //
429 
430  //
431  // We will get into trouble if we try to read more than we
432  // can map by one Vacb. So make sure that our lengths stay
433  // within a Vacb.
434  //
435 
436  if (TLength.LowPart > ReceivedLength) {
437  TLength.LowPart = ReceivedLength;
438  }
439 
440 
441  //
442  // Case 1 - Bcb was not found and Wait is TRUE.
443  //
444  // Note that it is important to minimize the time that the Bcb
445  // List spin lock is held, as well as guarantee we do not take
446  // any faults while holding this lock.
447  //
448  // If we can (and perhaps will) wait, then it is important to
449  // allocate the Bcb acquire it exclusive and free the Bcb List.
450  // We then proceed to read in the data, and anyone else finding
451  // our Bcb will have to wait shared to ensure that the data is
452  // in.
453  //
454 
455  if (FlagOn(Flags, PIN_WAIT)) {
456 
457  BcbOut = CcAllocateInitializeBcb( SharedCacheMap,
458  BcbOut,
459  &FOffset,
460  &TLength );
461 
462  if (BcbOut == NULL) {
463  DebugTrace( 0, 0, "Bcb allocation failure\n", 0 );
464  KeReleaseInStackQueuedSpinLock( &LockHandle );
465  SpinLockAcquired = FALSE;
466  ExRaiseStatus( STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES );
467  }
468 
469  //
470  // Now just acquire the newly-allocated Bcb shared, and
471  // release the spin lock.
472  //
473 
474  if (!ReadOnly) {
475  if (FlagOn(Flags, PIN_EXCLUSIVE)) {
476  (VOID)ExAcquireResourceExclusiveLite( &BcbOut->Resource, TRUE );
477  } else {
478  (VOID)ExAcquireSharedStarveExclusive( &BcbOut->Resource, TRUE );
479  }
480  }
481  KeReleaseInStackQueuedSpinLock( &LockHandle );
482  SpinLockAcquired = FALSE;
483 
484  //
485  // Now read in the data.
486  //
487 
488  if (!FlagOn(Flags, PIN_NO_READ)) {
489 
490  (VOID)CcMapAndRead( SharedCacheMap,
491  &FOffset,
492  TLength.LowPart,
493  ZeroFlags,
494  TRUE,
495  *BaseAddress );
496 
497  //
498  // Now we have to reacquire the Bcb List spinlock to load
499  // up the mapping if we are the first one, else we collided
500  // with someone else who loaded the mapping first, and we
501  // will just free our mapping. It is guaranteed that the
502  // data will be mapped to the same place.
503  //
504 
505  KeAcquireInStackQueuedSpinLock( &SharedCacheMap->BcbSpinLock, &LockHandle );
506 
507  if (BcbOut->BaseAddress == NULL) {
508 
509  BcbOut->BaseAddress = *BaseAddress;
510  BcbOut->Vacb = Vacb;
511  Vacb = NULL;
512  }
513 
514  KeReleaseInStackQueuedSpinLock( &LockHandle );
515 
516  //
517  // Calculate Base Address of the data we want.
518  //
519 
520  *BaseAddress = (PCHAR)BcbOut->BaseAddress +
521  (ULONG)( FileOffset->QuadPart - BcbOut->FileOffset.QuadPart );
522  }
523 
524  //
525  // Success!
526  //
527 
528  try_return( Result = TRUE );
529  }
530 
531 
532  //
533  // Case 2 - Bcb was not found and Wait is FALSE
534  //
535  // If we cannot wait, then we go immediately see if the data is
536  // there (CcMapAndRead), and then only set up the Bcb and release
537  // the spin lock if the data is there. Note here we call
538  // CcMapAndRead while holding the spin lock, because we know we
539  // will not fault and not block before returning.
540  //
541 
542  else {
543 
544  //
545  // Now try to allocate and initialize the Bcb. If we
546  // fail to allocate one, then return FALSE, since we know that
547  // Wait = FALSE. The caller may get lucky if he calls
548  // us back with Wait = TRUE.
549  //
550 
551  BcbOut = CcAllocateInitializeBcb( SharedCacheMap,
552  BcbOut,
553  &FOffset,
554  &TLength );
555 
556  if (BcbOut == NULL) {
557 
558  try_return( Result = FALSE );
559  }
560 
561  //
562  // If we are not ReadOnly, we must acquire the newly-allocated
563  // resource shared, and then we can free the spin lock.
564  //
565 
566  if (!ReadOnly) {
567  ExAcquireSharedStarveExclusive( &BcbOut->Resource, TRUE );
568  }
569  KeReleaseInStackQueuedSpinLock( &LockHandle );
570  SpinLockAcquired = FALSE;
571 
572  //
573  // Note that since this call has Wait = FALSE, it cannot
574  // get an exception (see procedure header).
575  //
576 
577  ASSERT( !FlagOn(Flags, PIN_NO_READ) );
578  if (!CcMapAndRead( SharedCacheMap,
579  &FOffset,
580  TLength.LowPart,
581  ZeroFlags,
582  FALSE,
583  *BaseAddress )) {
584 
585  try_return( Result = FALSE );
586  }
587 
588  //
589  // Now we have to reacquire the Bcb List spinlock to load
590  // up the mapping if we are the first one, else we collided
591  // with someone else who loaded the mapping first, and we
592  // will just free our mapping. It is guaranteed that the
593  // data will be mapped to the same place.
594  //
595 
596  KeAcquireInStackQueuedSpinLock( &SharedCacheMap->BcbSpinLock, &LockHandle );
597 
598  if (BcbOut->BaseAddress == NULL) {
599 
600  BcbOut->BaseAddress = *BaseAddress;
601  BcbOut->Vacb = Vacb;
602  Vacb = NULL;
603  }
604 
605  KeReleaseInStackQueuedSpinLock( &LockHandle );
606 
607  //
608  // Calculate Base Address of the data we want.
609  //
610 
611  *BaseAddress = (PCHAR)BcbOut->BaseAddress +
612  (ULONG)( FileOffset->QuadPart - BcbOut->FileOffset.QuadPart );
613 
614  //
615  // Success!
616  //
617 
618  try_return( Result = TRUE );
619  }
620 
621  } else {
622 
623  //
624  // We treat Bcbs as ReadOnly (do not acquire resource) if they
625  // are in sections for which we have not disabled modified writing.
626  //
627 
628  if (!FlagOn(SharedCacheMap->Flags, MODIFIED_WRITE_DISABLED)) {
629  ReadOnly = TRUE;
630  }
631  }
632 
633 
634  //
635  // Cases 3 and 4 - Bcb is there but not mapped
636  //
637 
638  if (BcbOut->BaseAddress == NULL) {
639 
640  //
641  // It is too complicated to attempt to calculate any ZeroFlags in this
642  // case, because we have to not only do the tests above, but also
643  // compare to the byte range in the Bcb since we will be passing
644  // those parameters to CcMapAndRead. Also, the probability of hitting
645  // some window where zeroing is of any advantage is quite small.
646  //
647 
648  //
649  // Set up to just reread the Bcb exactly as the data in it is
650  // described.
651  //
652 
653  *BaseAddress = ((PCHAR)*BaseAddress - (FileOffset->LowPart - BcbOut->FileOffset.LowPart));
654  FOffset = BcbOut->FileOffset;
655  TLength.QuadPart = (LONGLONG)BcbOut->ByteLength;
656 
657  //
658  // Case 3 - Bcb is there but not mapped and Wait is TRUE
659  //
660  // Increment the PinCount, and then release the BcbList
661  // SpinLock so that we can wait to acquire the Bcb exclusive.
662  // Once we have the Bcb exclusive, map and read it in if no
663  // one beats us to it. Someone may have beat us to it since
664  // we had to release the SpinLock above.
665  //
666 
667  if (FlagOn(Flags, PIN_WAIT)) {
668 
669  BcbOut->PinCount += 1;
670 
671  //
672  // Now we have to release the BcbList SpinLock in order to
673  // acquire the Bcb shared.
674  //
675 
676  KeReleaseInStackQueuedSpinLock( &LockHandle );
677  SpinLockAcquired = FALSE;
678  if (!ReadOnly) {
679  if (FlagOn(Flags, PIN_EXCLUSIVE)) {
680  (VOID)ExAcquireResourceExclusiveLite( &BcbOut->Resource, TRUE );
681  } else {
682  (VOID)ExAcquireSharedStarveExclusive( &BcbOut->Resource, TRUE );
683  }
684  }
685 
686  //
687  // Now proceed to map and read the data in.
688  //
689  // Now read in the data.
690  //
691 
692  if (!FlagOn(Flags, PIN_NO_READ)) {
693 
694  (VOID)CcMapAndRead( SharedCacheMap,
695  &FOffset,
696  TLength.LowPart,
697  ZeroFlags,
698  TRUE,
699  *BaseAddress );
700 
701  //
702  // Now we have to reacquire the Bcb List spinlock to load
703  // up the mapping if we are the first one, else we collided
704  // with someone else who loaded the mapping first, and we
705  // will just free our mapping. It is guaranteed that the
706  // data will be mapped to the same place.
707  //
708 
709  KeAcquireInStackQueuedSpinLock( &SharedCacheMap->BcbSpinLock, &LockHandle );
710 
711  if (BcbOut->BaseAddress == NULL) {
712 
713  BcbOut->BaseAddress = *BaseAddress;
714  BcbOut->Vacb = Vacb;
715  Vacb = NULL;
716  }
717 
718  KeReleaseInStackQueuedSpinLock( &LockHandle );
719 
720  //
721  //
722  // Calculate Base Address of the data we want.
723  //
724 
725  *BaseAddress = (PCHAR)BcbOut->BaseAddress +
726  (ULONG)( FileOffset->QuadPart - BcbOut->FileOffset.QuadPart );
727  }
728 
729  //
730  // Success!
731  //
732 
733  try_return( Result = TRUE );
734  }
735 
736 
737  //
738  // Case 4 - Bcb is there but not mapped, and Wait is FALSE
739  //
740  // Since we cannot wait, we go immediately see if the data is
741  // there (CcMapAndRead), and then only set up the Bcb and release
742  // the spin lock if the data is there. Note here we call
743  // CcMapAndRead while holding the spin lock, because we know we
744  // will not fault and not block before returning.
745  //
746 
747  else {
748 
749  if (!ReadOnly && !ExAcquireSharedStarveExclusive( &BcbOut->Resource, FALSE )) {
750 
751  //
752  // If we cannot get the resource and have not incremented PinCount, then
753  // suppress the unpin on cleanup.
754  //
755 
756  BcbOut = NULL;
757  try_return( Result = FALSE );
758  }
759 
760  BcbOut->PinCount += 1;
761 
762  KeReleaseInStackQueuedSpinLock( &LockHandle );
763  SpinLockAcquired = FALSE;
764 
765  //
766  // Note that since this call has Wait = FALSE, it cannot
767  // get an exception (see procedure header).
768  //
769 
770  ASSERT( !FlagOn(Flags, PIN_NO_READ) );
771  if (!CcMapAndRead( SharedCacheMap,
772  &BcbOut->FileOffset,
773  BcbOut->ByteLength,
774  ZeroFlags,
775  FALSE,
776  *BaseAddress )) {
777 
778  try_return( Result = FALSE );
779  }
780 
781  //
782  // Now we have to reacquire the Bcb List spinlock to load
783  // up the mapping if we are the first one, else we collided
784  // with someone else who loaded the mapping first, and we
785  // will just free our mapping. It is guaranteed that the
786  // data will be mapped to the same place.
787  //
788 
789  KeAcquireInStackQueuedSpinLock( &SharedCacheMap->BcbSpinLock, &LockHandle );
790 
791  if (BcbOut->BaseAddress == NULL) {
792 
793  BcbOut->BaseAddress = *BaseAddress;
794  BcbOut->Vacb = Vacb;
795  Vacb = NULL;
796  }
797 
798  KeReleaseInStackQueuedSpinLock( &LockHandle );
799 
800  //
801  // Calculate Base Address of the data we want.
802  //
803 
804  *BaseAddress = (PCHAR)BcbOut->BaseAddress +
805  (ULONG)( FileOffset->QuadPart - BcbOut->FileOffset.QuadPart );
806 
807  //
808  // Success!
809  //
810 
811  try_return( Result = TRUE );
812  }
813  }
814 
815 
816  //
817  // Cases 5 and 6 - Bcb is there and it is mapped
818  //
819 
820  else {
821 
822  //
823  // Case 5 - Bcb is there and mapped, and Wait is TRUE
824  //
825  // We can just increment the PinCount, release the SpinLock
826  // and then acquire the Bcb Shared if we are not ReadOnly.
827  //
828 
829  if (FlagOn(Flags, PIN_WAIT)) {
830 
831  BcbOut->PinCount += 1;
832  KeReleaseInStackQueuedSpinLock( &LockHandle );
833  SpinLockAcquired = FALSE;
834 
835  //
836  // Acquire Bcb Resource shared to ensure that it is in memory.
837  //
838 
839  if (!ReadOnly) {
840  if (FlagOn(Flags, PIN_EXCLUSIVE)) {
841  (VOID)ExAcquireResourceExclusiveLite( &BcbOut->Resource, TRUE );
842  } else {
843  (VOID)ExAcquireSharedStarveExclusive( &BcbOut->Resource, TRUE );
844  }
845  }
846  }
847 
848  //
849  // Case 6 - Bcb is there and mapped, and Wait is FALSE
850  //
851  // If we are not ReadOnly, we have to first see if we can
852  // acquire the Bcb shared before incrementing the PinCount,
853  // since we will have to return FALSE if we cannot acquire the
854  // resource.
855  //
856 
857  else {
858 
859  //
860  // Acquire Bcb Resource shared to ensure that it is in memory.
861  //
862 
863  if (!ReadOnly && !ExAcquireSharedStarveExclusive( &BcbOut->Resource, FALSE )) {
864 
865  //
866  // If we cannot get the resource and have not incremented PinCount, then
867  // suppress the unpin on cleanup.
868  //
869 
870  BcbOut = NULL;
871  try_return( Result = FALSE );
872  }
873 
874  BcbOut->PinCount += 1;
875  KeReleaseInStackQueuedSpinLock( &LockHandle );
876  SpinLockAcquired = FALSE;
877  }
878 
879  //
880  // Calculate Base Address of the data we want.
881  //
882 
883  *BaseAddress = (PCHAR)BcbOut->BaseAddress +
884  (ULONG)( FileOffset->QuadPart - BcbOut->FileOffset.QuadPart );
885 
886  //
887  // Success!
888  //
889 
890  try_return( Result = TRUE );
891  }
892 
893 
894  try_exit: NOTHING;
895 
896  if (FlagOn(Flags, PIN_NO_READ) &&
897  FlagOn(Flags, PIN_EXCLUSIVE) &&
898  (BcbOut != NULL) &&
899  (BcbOut->BaseAddress != NULL)) {
900 
901  //
902  // Unmap the Vacb and free the resource if the Bcb is still
903  // dirty. We have to free the resource before dropping the
904  // spinlock, and we want to hold the resource until the
905  // virtual address is freed.
906  //
907 
908  CcFreeVirtualAddress( BcbOut->Vacb );
909 
910  BcbOut->BaseAddress = NULL;
911  BcbOut->Vacb = NULL;
912  }
913 
914  } finally {
915 
916  //
917  // Release the spinlock if it is acquired.
918  //
919 
920  if (SpinLockAcquired) {
921  KeReleaseInStackQueuedSpinLock( &LockHandle );
922  }
923 
924  //
925  // If the Vacb was not used for any reason (error or not needed), then free it here.
926  //
927 
928  if (Vacb != NULL) {
929  CcFreeVirtualAddress( Vacb );
930  }
931 
932  //
933  // If we referenced a piece of a multilevel structure, release here.
934  //
935 
936  if (FlagOn(Flags, PIN_NO_READ)) {
937 
938  CcDereferenceFileOffset( SharedCacheMap, *FileOffset );
939  }
940 
941  if (Result) {
942 
943  *Bcb = BcbOut;
944  *BeyondLastByte = BcbOut->BeyondLastByte;
945 
946  //
947  // An abnormal termination can occur on an allocation failure,
948  // or on a failure to map and read the buffer.
949  //
950 
951  } else {
952 
953  *BaseAddress = NULL;
954  if (BcbOut != NULL) {
955  CcUnpinFileData( BcbOut, ReadOnly, UNPIN );
956  }
957  }
958 
959  DebugTrace( 0, me, " <Bcb = %08lx\n", *Bcb );
960  DebugTrace( 0, me, " <BaseAddress = %08lx\n", *BaseAddress );
961  DebugTrace(-1, me, "CcPinFileData -> %02lx\n", Result );
962  }
963 
964  return Result;
965 }
966 
967 
968 //
969 // Internal Support Routine
970 //
971 
972 VOID
973 FASTCALL
974 CcUnpinFileDataEx (
975  IN OUT PBCB Bcb,
976  IN BOOLEAN ReadOnly,
977  IN UNMAP_ACTIONS UnmapAction
978  )
979 
980 /*++
981 
982 Routine Description:
983 
984  This routine umaps and unlocks the specified buffer, which was previously
985  locked and mapped by calling CcPinFileData.
986 
987 Arguments:
988 
989  Bcb - Pointer previously returned from CcPinFileData. As may be
990  seen above, this pointer may be either a Bcb or a Vacb.
991 
992  ReadOnly - must specify same value as when data was mapped
993 
994  UnmapAction - UNPIN or SET_CLEAN
995 
996 Return Value:
997 
998  None
999 
1000 --*/
1001 
1002 {
1003  KLOCK_QUEUE_HANDLE LockHandle;
1004  PSHARED_CACHE_MAP SharedCacheMap;
1005 
1006  DebugTrace(+1, me, "CcUnpinFileData >Bcb = %08lx\n", Bcb );
1007 
1008  //
1009  // Note, since we have to allocate so many Vacbs, we do not use
1010  // a node type code. However, the Vacb starts with a BaseAddress,
1011  // so we assume that the low byte of the Bcb node type code has
1012  // some bits set, which a page-aligned Base Address cannot.
1013  //
1014 
1015  ASSERT( (CACHE_NTC_BCB & 0xFF) != 0 );
1016 
1017  if (Bcb->NodeTypeCode != CACHE_NTC_BCB) {
1018 
1019  ASSERT(((PVACB)Bcb >= CcVacbs) && ((PVACB)Bcb < CcBeyondVacbs));
1020  ASSERT(((PVACB)Bcb)->SharedCacheMap->NodeTypeCode == CACHE_NTC_SHARED_CACHE_MAP);
1021 
1022  CcFreeVirtualAddress( (PVACB)Bcb );
1023 
1024  DebugTrace(-1, me, "CcUnpinFileData -> VOID (simple release)\n", 0 );
1025 
1026  return;
1027  }
1028 
1029  SharedCacheMap = Bcb->SharedCacheMap;
1030 
1031  //
1032  // We treat Bcbs as ReadOnly (do not acquire resource) if they
1033  // are in sections for which we have not disabled modified writing, or
1034  // in this special case if this action is a dereferencing of the BCB.
1035  //
1036 
1037  if (!FlagOn(SharedCacheMap->Flags, MODIFIED_WRITE_DISABLED) ||
1038  UnmapAction == UNREF) {
1039  ReadOnly = TRUE;
1040  }
1041 
1042  //
1043  // Synchronize
1044  //
1045 
1046  KeAcquireInStackQueuedSpinLock( &SharedCacheMap->BcbSpinLock, &LockHandle );
1047 
1048  switch (UnmapAction) {
1049 
1050  case UNPIN:
1051  case UNREF:
1052 
1053  ASSERT( Bcb->PinCount > 0 );
1054 
1055  Bcb->PinCount -= 1;
1056 
1057  break;
1058 
1059  case SET_CLEAN:
1060 
1061  if (Bcb->Dirty) {
1062 
1063  ULONG Pages = Bcb->ByteLength >> PAGE_SHIFT;
1064 
1065  //
1066  // Reverse the rest of the actions taken when the Bcb was set dirty.
1067  //
1068 
1069  Bcb->Dirty = FALSE;
1070 
1071  //
1072  // Clear any Lsn that was assigned to this Bcb.
1073  //
1074 
1075  Bcb->OldestLsn.QuadPart = 0;
1076  Bcb->NewestLsn.QuadPart = 0;
1077 
1078  CcAcquireMasterLockAtDpcLevel();
1079  CcDeductDirtyPages( SharedCacheMap, Pages );
1080 
1081  //
1082  // Normally we need to reduce CcPagesYetToWrite appropriately.
1083  //
1084 
1085  if (CcPagesYetToWrite > Pages) {
1086  CcPagesYetToWrite -= Pages;
1087  } else {
1088  CcPagesYetToWrite = 0;
1089  }
1090 
1091  //
1092  // Remove SharedCacheMap from dirty list if nothing more dirty,
1093  // and someone still has the cache map opened.
1094  //
1095 
1096  if ((SharedCacheMap->DirtyPages == 0) &&
1097  (SharedCacheMap->OpenCount != 0)) {
1098 
1099  RemoveEntryList( &SharedCacheMap->SharedCacheMapLinks );
1100  CcInsertIntoCleanSharedCacheMapList( SharedCacheMap );
1101  }
1102 
1103  CcReleaseMasterLockFromDpcLevel();
1104  }
1105 
1106  break;
1107 
1108  default:
1109  CcBugCheck( UnmapAction, 0, 0 );
1110  }
1111 
1112  //
1113  // If we brought it to 0, then we have to kill it.
1114  //
1115 
1116  if (Bcb->PinCount == 0) {
1117 
1118  //
1119  // If the Bcb is Dirty, we only release the resource and unmap now.
1120  //
1121 
1122  if (Bcb->Dirty) {
1123 
1124  if (Bcb->BaseAddress != NULL) {
1125 
1126  //
1127  // Unmap the Vacb and free the resource if the Bcb is still
1128  // dirty. We have to free the resource before dropping the
1129  // spinlock, and we want to hold the resource until the
1130  // virtual address is freed.
1131  //
1132 
1133  CcFreeVirtualAddress( Bcb->Vacb );
1134 
1135  Bcb->BaseAddress = NULL;
1136  Bcb->Vacb = NULL;
1137  }
1138 
1139  if (!ReadOnly) {
1140  ExReleaseResourceLite( &Bcb->Resource );
1141  }
1142 
1143  KeReleaseInStackQueuedSpinLock( &LockHandle );
1144  }
1145 
1146  //
1147  // Otherwise, we also delete the Bcb.
1148  //
1149 
1150  else {
1151 
1152  //
1153  // Since CcCalculateVacbLockCount has to be able to walk
1154  // the BcbList with only the VacbSpinLock, we take that one
1155  // out to change the list and decrement the level.
1156  //
1157 
1158  CcAcquireVacbLockAtDpcLevel();
1159  RemoveEntryList( &Bcb->BcbLinks );
1160 
1161  //
1162  // For large metadata streams we unlock the Vacb level.
1163  //
1164 
1165  CcUnlockVacbLevel( SharedCacheMap, Bcb->FileOffset.QuadPart );
1166  CcReleaseVacbLockFromDpcLevel();
1167 
1168  if (Bcb->BaseAddress != NULL) {
1169 
1170  CcFreeVirtualAddress( Bcb->Vacb );
1171  }
1172 #if DBG
1173  if (!ReadOnly) {
1174  ExReleaseResourceLite( &Bcb->Resource );
1175  }
1176 
1177  //
1178  // ASSERT that the resource is unowned.
1179  //
1180 
1181  ASSERT( Bcb->Resource.ActiveCount == 0 );
1182 #endif
1183  KeReleaseInStackQueuedSpinLock( &LockHandle );
1184  CcDeallocateBcb( Bcb );
1185  }
1186  }
1187 
1188  //
1189  // Else we just have to release our Shared access, if we are not
1190  // readonly. We don't need to do this above, since we deallocate
1191  // the entire Bcb there.
1192  //
1193 
1194  else {
1195 
1196  if (!ReadOnly) {
1197  ExReleaseResourceLite( &Bcb->Resource );
1198  }
1199 
1200  KeReleaseInStackQueuedSpinLock( &LockHandle );
1201  }
1202 
1203  DebugTrace(-1, me, "CcUnpinFileData -> VOID\n", 0 );
1204 
1205  return;
1206 }

1209 VOID
1210 CcSetReadAheadGranularity (
1211  __in PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
1212  __in ULONG Granularity
1213  )
1214 
1215 /*++
1216 
1217 Routine Description:
1218 
1219  This routine may be called to set the read ahead granularity used by
1220  the Cache Manager. The default is PAGE_SIZE. The number is decremented
1221  and stored as a mask.
1222 
1223 Arguments:
1224 
1225  FileObject - File Object for which granularity shall be set
1226 
1227  Granularity - new granularity, which must be an even power of 2 and
1228  >= PAGE_SIZE
1229 
1230 Return Value:
1231 
1232  None
1233 --*/
1234 
1235 {
1236  ((PPRIVATE_CACHE_MAP)FileObject->PrivateCacheMap)->ReadAheadMask = Granularity - 1;
1237 }
1238 
1239 
1240 VOID
1241 CcScheduleReadAhead (
1242  __in PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
1243  __in PLARGE_INTEGER FileOffset,
1244  __in ULONG Length
1245  )
1246 
1247 /*++
1248 
1249 Routine Description:
1250 
1251  This routine is called by Copy Read and Mdl Read file system routines to
1252  perform common Read Ahead processing. The input parameters describe
1253  the current read which has just been completed, or perhaps only started
1254  in the case of Mdl Reads. Based on these parameters, an
1255  assessment is made on how much data should be read ahead, and whether
1256  that data has already been read ahead.
1257 
1258  The processing is divided into two parts:
1259 
1260  CALCULATE READ AHEAD REQUIREMENTS (CcScheduleReadAhead)
1261 
1262  PERFORM READ AHEAD (CcPerformReadAhead)
1263 
1264  File systems should always call CcReadAhead, which will conditionally
1265  call CcScheduleReadAhead (if the read is large enough). If such a call
1266  determines that there is read ahead work to do, and no read ahead is
1267  currently active, then it will set ReadAheadActive and schedule read
1268  ahead to be performed by the Lazy Writer, who will call CcPeformReadAhead.
1269 
1270 Arguments:
1271 
1272  FileObject - supplies pointer to FileObject on which readahead should be
1273  considered.
1274 
1275  FileOffset - supplies the FileOffset at which the last read just occurred.
1276 
1277  Length - supplies the length of the last read.
1278 
1279 Return Value:
1280 
1281  None
1282 --*/
1283 
1284 {
1285  LARGE_INTEGER NewOffset;
1286  LARGE_INTEGER NewBeyond;
1287  LARGE_INTEGER FileOffset1, FileOffset2;
1288  KIRQL OldIrql;
1289  PSHARED_CACHE_MAP SharedCacheMap;
1290  PPRIVATE_CACHE_MAP PrivateCacheMap;
1291  PWORK_QUEUE_ENTRY WorkQueueEntry;
1292  ULONG ReadAheadSize;
1293  LOGICAL Changed = FALSE;
1294 
1295  DebugTrace(+1, me, "CcScheduleReadAhead:\n", 0 );
1296  DebugTrace2(0, me, " FileOffset = %08lx, %08lx\n", FileOffset->LowPart,
1297  FileOffset->HighPart );
1298  DebugTrace( 0, me, " Length = %08lx\n", Length );
1299 
1300  SharedCacheMap = FileObject->SectionObjectPointer->SharedCacheMap;
1301  PrivateCacheMap = FileObject->PrivateCacheMap;
1302 
1303  if ((PrivateCacheMap == NULL) ||
1304  (SharedCacheMap == NULL) ||
1305  FlagOn(SharedCacheMap->Flags, DISABLE_READ_AHEAD)) {
1306 
1307  DebugTrace(-1, me, "CcScheduleReadAhead -> VOID (Nooped)\n", 0 );
1308 
1309  return;
1310  }
1311 
1312  //
1313  // Round boundaries of transfer up to some greater granularity, so that
1314  // sequential reads will be recognized even if a few bytes are skipped
1315  // between records.
1316  //
1317 
1318  NewOffset = *FileOffset;
1319  NewBeyond.QuadPart = FileOffset->QuadPart + (LONGLONG)Length;
1320 
1321  //
1322  // Find the next read ahead boundary beyond the current read.
1323  //
1324 
1325  ReadAheadSize = (Length + PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadMask) & ~PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadMask;
1326  FileOffset2.QuadPart = NewBeyond.QuadPart + (LONGLONG)ReadAheadSize;
1327  FileOffset2.LowPart &= ~PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadMask;
1328 
1329  //
1330  // CALCULATE READ AHEAD REQUIREMENTS
1331  //
1332 
1333  //
1334  // Take out the ReadAhead spinlock to synchronize our read ahead decision.
1335  //
1336 
1337  ExAcquireSpinLock( &PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadSpinLock, &OldIrql );
1338 
1339  //
1340  // Read Ahead Case 0.
1341  //
1342  // Sequential-only hint in the file object. For this case we will
1343  // try and always keep two read ahead granularities read ahead from
1344  // and including the end of the current transfer. This case has the
1345  // lowest overhead, and the code is completely immune to how the
1346  // caller skips around. Sequential files use ReadAheadOffset[1] in
1347  // the PrivateCacheMap as their "high water mark".
1348  //
1349 
1350  if (FlagOn(FileObject->Flags, FO_SEQUENTIAL_ONLY)) {
1351 
1352  //
1353  // If the next boundary is greater than or equal to the high-water mark,
1354  // then read ahead.
1355  //
1356 
1357  if (FileOffset2.QuadPart >= PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadOffset[1].QuadPart) {
1358 
1359  //
1360  // On the first read if we are using a large read ahead granularity,
1361  // and the read did not get it all, we will just get the rest of the
1362  // first data we want.
1363  //
1364 
1365  if ((FileOffset->QuadPart == 0)
1366 
1367  &&
1368 
1369  (PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadMask > (PAGE_SIZE - 1))
1370 
1371  &&
1372 
1373  ((Length + PAGE_SIZE - 1) <= PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadMask)) {
1374 
1375  FileOffset1.QuadPart = (LONGLONG)( ROUND_TO_PAGES(Length) );
1376  PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadLength[0] = ReadAheadSize - FileOffset1.LowPart;
1377  FileOffset2.QuadPart = (LONGLONG)ReadAheadSize;
1378 
1379  //
1380  // Calculate the next read ahead boundary.
1381  //
1382 
1383  } else {
1384 
1385  FileOffset1.QuadPart = PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadOffset[1].QuadPart +
1386  (LONGLONG)ReadAheadSize;
1387 
1388  //
1389  // If the end of the current read is actually beyond where we would
1390  // normally do our read ahead, then we have fallen behind, and we must
1391  // advance to that spot.
1392  //
1393 
1394  if (FileOffset2.QuadPart > FileOffset1.QuadPart) {
1395  FileOffset1 = FileOffset2;
1396  }
1397  PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadLength[0] = ReadAheadSize;
1398  FileOffset2.QuadPart = FileOffset1.QuadPart + (LONGLONG)ReadAheadSize;
1399  }
1400 
1401  //
1402  // Now issue the next two read aheads.
1403  //
1404 
1405  PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadOffset[0] = FileOffset1;
1406 
1407  PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadOffset[1] = FileOffset2;
1408  PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadLength[1] = ReadAheadSize;
1409 
1410  Changed = TRUE;
1411  }
1412 
1413  //
1414  // Read Ahead Case 1.
1415  //
1416  // If this is the third of three sequential reads, then we will see if
1417  // we can read ahead. Note that if the first read to a file is to
1418  // offset 0, it passes this test.
1419  //
1420 
1421  } else if ((NewOffset.HighPart == PrivateCacheMap->BeyondLastByte2.HighPart)
1422 
1423  &&
1424 
1425  ((NewOffset.LowPart & ~NOISE_BITS)
1426  == (PrivateCacheMap->BeyondLastByte2.LowPart & ~NOISE_BITS))
1427 
1428  &&
1429 
1430  (PrivateCacheMap->FileOffset2.HighPart
1431  == PrivateCacheMap->BeyondLastByte1.HighPart)
1432 
1433  &&
1434 
1435  ((PrivateCacheMap->FileOffset2.LowPart & ~NOISE_BITS)
1436  == (PrivateCacheMap->BeyondLastByte1.LowPart & ~NOISE_BITS))) {
1437 
1438  //
1439  // On the first read if we are using a large read ahead granularity,
1440  // and the read did not get it all, we will just get the rest of the
1441  // first data we want.
1442  //
1443 
1444  if ((FileOffset->QuadPart == 0)
1445 
1446  &&
1447 
1448  (PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadMask > (PAGE_SIZE - 1))
1449 
1450  &&
1451 
1452  ((Length + PAGE_SIZE - 1) <= PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadMask)) {
1453 
1454  FileOffset2.QuadPart = (LONGLONG)( ROUND_TO_PAGES(Length) );
1455  }
1456 
1457  //
1458  // Round read offset to next read ahead boundary.
1459  //
1460 
1461  else {
1462  FileOffset2.QuadPart = NewBeyond.QuadPart + (LONGLONG)ReadAheadSize;
1463 
1464  FileOffset2.LowPart &= ~PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadMask;
1465  }
1466 
1467  //
1468  // Set read ahead length to be the same as for the most recent read,
1469  // up to our max.
1470  //
1471 
1472  if (FileOffset2.QuadPart != PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadOffset[1].QuadPart) {
1473 
1474  ASSERT( FileOffset2.HighPart >= 0 );
1475 
1476  Changed = TRUE;
1477  PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadOffset[1] = FileOffset2;
1478  PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadLength[1] = ReadAheadSize;
1479  }
1480  }
1481 
1482  //
1483  // Read Ahead Case 2.
1484  //
1485  // If this is the third read following a particular stride, then we
1486  // will see if we can read ahead. One example of an application that
1487  // might do this is a spreadsheet. Note that this code even works
1488  // for negative strides.
1489  //
1490 
1491  else if ( ( NewOffset.QuadPart -
1492  PrivateCacheMap->FileOffset2.QuadPart ) ==
1493  ( PrivateCacheMap->FileOffset2.QuadPart -
1494  PrivateCacheMap->FileOffset1.QuadPart )) {
1495 
1496  //
1497  // According to the current stride, the next offset will be:
1498  //
1499  // NewOffset + (NewOffset - FileOffset2)
1500  //
1501  // which is the same as:
1502  //
1503  // (NewOffset * 2) - FileOffset2
1504  //
1505 
1506  FileOffset2.QuadPart = ( NewOffset.QuadPart << 1 ) - PrivateCacheMap->FileOffset2.QuadPart;
1507 
1508  //
1509  // If our stride is going backwards through the file, we
1510  // have to detect the case where the next step would wrap.
1511  //
1512 
1513  if (FileOffset2.HighPart >= 0) {
1514 
1515  //
1516  // The read ahead length must be extended by the same amount that
1517  // we will round the PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadOffset down.
1518  //
1519 
1520  Length += FileOffset2.LowPart & (PAGE_SIZE - 1);
1521 
1522  //
1523  // Now round the PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadOffset down.
1524  //
1525 
1526  FileOffset2.LowPart &= ~(PAGE_SIZE - 1);
1527  PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadOffset[1] = FileOffset2;
1528 
1529  //
1530  // Round to page boundary.
1531  //
1532 
1533  PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadLength[1] = (ULONG) ROUND_TO_PAGES(Length);
1534  Changed = TRUE;
1535  }
1536  }
1537 
1538  //
1539  // Get out if the ReadAhead requirements did not change.
1540  //
1541 
1542  if (!Changed || PrivateCacheMap->Flags.ReadAheadActive) {
1543 
1544  DebugTrace( 0, me, "Read ahead already in progress or no change\n", 0 );
1545 
1546  ExReleaseSpinLock( &PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadSpinLock, OldIrql );
1547  return;
1548  }
1549 
1550  //
1551  // Otherwise, we will proceed and try to schedule the read ahead
1552  // ourselves.
1553  //
1554 
1555  CC_SET_PRIVATE_CACHE_MAP (PrivateCacheMap, PRIVATE_CACHE_MAP_READ_AHEAD_ACTIVE);
1556 
1557  //
1558  // Release spin lock on way out
1559  //
1560 
1561  ExReleaseSpinLock( &PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadSpinLock, OldIrql );
1562 
1563  //
1564  // Queue the read ahead request to the Lazy Writer's work queue.
1565  //
1566 
1567  DebugTrace( 0, me, "Queueing read ahead to worker thread\n", 0 );
1568 
1569  WorkQueueEntry = CcAllocateWorkQueueEntry();
1570 
1571  //
1572  // If we failed to allocate a work queue entry, then, we will
1573  // quietly bag it. Read ahead is only an optimization, and
1574  // no one ever requires that it occur.
1575  //
1576 
1577  if (WorkQueueEntry != NULL) {
1578 
1579  //
1580  // We must reference this file object so that it cannot go away
1581  // until we finish Read Ahead processing in the Worker Thread.
1582  //
1583 
1584  ObReferenceObject ( FileObject );
1585 
1586  //
1587  // Increment open count to make sure the SharedCacheMap stays around.
1588  //
1589 
1590  CcAcquireMasterLock( &OldIrql );
1591  CcIncrementOpenCount( SharedCacheMap, 'adRQ' );
1592  SetFlag(SharedCacheMap->Flags, READ_AHEAD_QUEUED);
1593  CcReleaseMasterLock( OldIrql );
1594 
1595  WorkQueueEntry->Function = (UCHAR)ReadAhead;
1596  WorkQueueEntry->Parameters.Read.FileObject = FileObject;
1597 
1598  CcPostWorkQueue( WorkQueueEntry, &CcExpressWorkQueue );
1599  }
1600 
1601  //
1602  // If we failed to allocate a Work Queue Entry, or all of the pages
1603  // are resident we must set the active flag false.
1604  //
1605 
1606  else {
1607 
1608  ExAcquireFastLock( &PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadSpinLock, &OldIrql );
1609  CC_CLEAR_PRIVATE_CACHE_MAP (PrivateCacheMap, PRIVATE_CACHE_MAP_READ_AHEAD_ACTIVE);
1610  ExReleaseFastLock( &PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadSpinLock, OldIrql );
1611  }
1612 
1613  DebugTrace(-1, me, "CcScheduleReadAhead -> VOID\n", 0 );
1614 
1615  return;
1616 }
1617 
1618 
1619 VOID
1620 FASTCALL
1621 CcPerformReadAhead (
1622  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject
1623  )
1624 
1625 /*++
1626 
1627 Routine Description:
1628 
1629  This routine is called by the Lazy Writer to perform read ahead which
1630  has been scheduled for this file by CcScheduleReadAhead.
1631 
1632 Arguments:
1633 
1634  FileObject - supplies pointer to FileObject on which readahead should be
1635  considered.
1636 
1637 Return Value:
1638 
1639  None
1640 --*/
1641 
1642 {
1643  KIRQL OldIrql;
1644  PSHARED_CACHE_MAP SharedCacheMap;
1645  PPRIVATE_CACHE_MAP PrivateCacheMap;
1646  ULONG i;
1647  LARGE_INTEGER ReadAheadOffset[2];
1648  ULONG ReadAheadLength[2];
1649  PCACHE_MANAGER_CALLBACKS Callbacks;
1650  PVOID Context;
1651  ULONG SavedState;
1652  LOGICAL Done;
1653  LOGICAL HitEof = FALSE;
1654  LOGICAL ReadAheadPerformed = FALSE;
1655  ULONG FaultOccurred = 0;
1656  PETHREAD Thread = PsGetCurrentThread();
1657  PVACB Vacb = NULL;
1658 
1659  LOGICAL ResourceHeld = FALSE;
1660 
1661  DebugTrace(+1, me, "CcPerformReadAhead:\n", 0 );
1662  DebugTrace( 0, me, " FileObject = %08lx\n", FileObject );
1663 
1664  MmSavePageFaultReadAhead( Thread, &SavedState );
1665 
1666  try {
1667 
1668  //
1669  // Since we have the open count biased, we can safely access the
1670  // SharedCacheMap.
1671  //
1672 
1673  SharedCacheMap = FileObject->SectionObjectPointer->SharedCacheMap;
1674 
1675  Callbacks = SharedCacheMap->Callbacks;
1676  Context = SharedCacheMap->LazyWriteContext;
1677 
1678  //
1679  // After the first time, keep looping as long as there are new
1680  // read ahead requirements. (We will skip out below.)
1681  //
1682 
1683  while (TRUE) {
1684 
1685  //
1686  // Get SharedCacheMap and PrivateCacheMap. If either are now NULL, get
1687  // out.
1688  //
1689 
1690  CcAcquireMasterLock( &OldIrql );
1691 
1692  PrivateCacheMap = FileObject->PrivateCacheMap;
1693 
1694  //
1695  // Now capture the information that we need, so that we can drop the
1696  // SharedList Resource. This information is advisory only anyway, and
1697  // the caller must guarantee that the FileObject is referenced.
1698  //
1699 
1700  if (PrivateCacheMap != NULL) {
1701 
1702  ExAcquireSpinLockAtDpcLevel( &PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadSpinLock );
1703 
1704  //
1705  // We are done when the lengths are 0
1706  //
1707 
1708  Done = ((PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadLength[0] |
1709  PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadLength[1]) == 0);
1710 
1711  ReadAheadOffset[0] = PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadOffset[0];
1712  ReadAheadOffset[1] = PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadOffset[1];
1713  ReadAheadLength[0] = PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadLength[0];
1714  ReadAheadLength[1] = PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadLength[1];
1715  PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadLength[0] = 0;
1716  PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadLength[1] = 0;
1717 
1718  ExReleaseSpinLockFromDpcLevel( &PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadSpinLock );
1719  }
1720 
1721  CcReleaseMasterLock( OldIrql );
1722 
1723  //
1724  // Acquire the file shared.
1725  //
1726 
1727  ResourceHeld = (*Callbacks->AcquireForReadAhead)( Context, TRUE );
1728 
1729  if ((PrivateCacheMap == NULL) || Done || !ResourceHeld) {
1730 
1731  try_return( NOTHING );
1732  }
1733 
1734  //
1735  // PERFORM READ AHEAD
1736  //
1737  //
1738  // Now loop until everything is read in. The Read ahead is accomplished
1739  // by touching the pages with an appropriate ReadAhead parameter in MM.
1740  //
1741 
1742  i = 0;
1743 
1744  do {
1745 
1746  LARGE_INTEGER Offset, SavedOffset;
1747  ULONG Length, SavedLength;
1748 
1749  Offset = ReadAheadOffset[i];
1750  Length = ReadAheadLength[i];
1751  SavedOffset = Offset;
1752  SavedLength = Length;
1753 
1754  if ((Length != 0)
1755 
1756  &&
1757 
1758  ( Offset.QuadPart <= SharedCacheMap->FileSize.QuadPart )) {
1759 
1760  ReadAheadPerformed = TRUE;
1761 
1762  //
1763  // Keep length within file and MAX_READ_AHEAD
1764  //
1765 
1766  if ( ( Offset.QuadPart + (LONGLONG)Length ) >= SharedCacheMap->FileSize.QuadPart ) {
1767 
1768  Length = (ULONG)( SharedCacheMap->FileSize.QuadPart - Offset.QuadPart );
1769  HitEof = TRUE;
1770 
1771  }
1772  if (Length > MAX_READ_AHEAD) {
1773  Length = MAX_READ_AHEAD;
1774  }
1775 
1776  //
1777  // Now loop to read all of the desired data in. This loop
1778  // is more or less like the same loop to read data in
1779  // CcCopyRead, except that we do not copy anything, just
1780  // unmap as soon as it is in.
1781  //
1782 
1783  while (Length != 0) {
1784 
1785  ULONG ReceivedLength;
1786  PVOID CacheBuffer;
1787  ULONG PagesToGo;
1788 
1789  //
1790  // Call local routine to Map or Access the file data.
1791  // If we cannot map the data because of a Wait condition,
1792  // return FALSE.
1793  //
1794  // Since this routine is intended to be called from
1795  // the finally handler from file system read modules,
1796  // it is imperative that it not raise any exceptions.
1797  // Therefore, if any expected exception is raised, we
1798  // will simply get out.
1799  //
1800 
1801  CacheBuffer = CcGetVirtualAddress( SharedCacheMap,
1802  Offset,
1803  &Vacb,
1804  &ReceivedLength );
1805 
1806  //
1807  // If we got more than we need, make sure to only transfer
1808  // the right amount.
1809  //
1810 
1811  if (ReceivedLength > Length) {
1812  ReceivedLength = Length;
1813  }
1814 
1815  //
1816  // Now loop to touch all of the pages, calling MM to ensure
1817  // that if we fault, we take in exactly the number of pages
1818  // we need.
1819  //
1820 
1821  PagesToGo = ADDRESS_AND_SIZE_TO_SPAN_PAGES( CacheBuffer,
1822  ReceivedLength );
1823 
1824  CcMissCounter = &CcReadAheadIos;
1825 
1826  while (PagesToGo) {
1827 
1828  MmSetPageFaultReadAhead( Thread, (PagesToGo - 1) );
1829  FaultOccurred |= !MmCheckCachedPageState(CacheBuffer, FALSE);
1830 
1831  CacheBuffer = (PCHAR)CacheBuffer + PAGE_SIZE;
1832  PagesToGo -= 1;
1833  }
1834  CcMissCounter = &CcThrowAway;
1835 
1836  //
1837  // Calculate how much data we have left to go.
1838  //
1839 
1840  Length -= ReceivedLength;
1841 
1842  //
1843  // Assume we did not get all the data we wanted, and set
1844  // Offset to the end of the returned data.
1845  //
1846 
1847  Offset.QuadPart = Offset.QuadPart + (LONGLONG)ReceivedLength;
1848 
1849  //
1850  // It was only a page, so we can just leave this loop
1851  // After freeing the address.
1852  //
1853 
1854  CcFreeVirtualAddress( Vacb );
1855  Vacb = NULL;
1856  }
1857  }
1858  i += 1;
1859  } while (i <= 1);
1860 
1861  //
1862  // Release the file
1863  //
1864 
1865  (*Callbacks->ReleaseFromReadAhead)( Context );
1866  ResourceHeld = FALSE;
1867  }
1868 
1869  try_exit: NOTHING;
1870  }
1871  finally {
1872 
1873  MmResetPageFaultReadAhead(Thread, SavedState);
1874  CcMissCounter = &CcThrowAway;
1875 
1876  //
1877  // If we got an error faulting a single page in, release the Vacb
1878  // here. It is important to free any mapping before dropping the
1879  // resource to prevent purge problems.
1880  //
1881 
1882  if (Vacb != NULL) {
1883  CcFreeVirtualAddress( Vacb );
1884  }
1885 
1886  //
1887  // Release the file
1888  //
1889 
1890  if (ResourceHeld) {
1891  (*Callbacks->ReleaseFromReadAhead)( Context );
1892  }
1893 
1894  //
1895  // To show we are done, we must make sure the PrivateCacheMap is
1896  // still there.
1897  //
1898 
1899  CcAcquireMasterLock( &OldIrql );
1900 
1901  PrivateCacheMap = FileObject->PrivateCacheMap;
1902 
1903  //
1904  // Show readahead is going inactive.
1905  //
1906 
1907  if (PrivateCacheMap != NULL) {
1908 
1909  ExAcquireSpinLockAtDpcLevel( &PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadSpinLock );
1910  CC_CLEAR_PRIVATE_CACHE_MAP (PrivateCacheMap, PRIVATE_CACHE_MAP_READ_AHEAD_ACTIVE);
1911 
1912  //
1913  // If he said sequential only and we smashed into Eof, then
1914  // let's reset the highwater mark in case he wants to read the
1915  // file sequentially again.
1916  //
1917 
1918  if (HitEof && FlagOn(FileObject->Flags, FO_SEQUENTIAL_ONLY)) {
1919  PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadOffset[1].LowPart =
1920  PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadOffset[1].HighPart = 0;
1921  }
1922 
1923  //
1924  // If no faults occurred, turn read ahead off.
1925  //
1926 
1927  if (ReadAheadPerformed && !FaultOccurred) {
1928  CC_CLEAR_PRIVATE_CACHE_MAP (PrivateCacheMap, PRIVATE_CACHE_MAP_READ_AHEAD_ENABLED);
1929  }
1930 
1931  ExReleaseSpinLockFromDpcLevel( &PrivateCacheMap->ReadAheadSpinLock );
1932  }
1933 
1934  //
1935  // Free SharedCacheMap list
1936  //
1937 
1938  CcReleaseMasterLock( OldIrql );
1939 
1940  ObDereferenceObject( FileObject );
1941 
1942  //
1943  // Serialize again to decrement the open count.
1944  //
1945 
1946  CcAcquireMasterLock( &OldIrql );
1947 
1948  CcDecrementOpenCount( SharedCacheMap, 'adRP' );
1949 
1950  ClearFlag(SharedCacheMap->Flags, READ_AHEAD_QUEUED);
1951 
1952  if ((SharedCacheMap->OpenCount == 0) &&
1953  !FlagOn(SharedCacheMap->Flags, WRITE_QUEUED) &&
1954  (SharedCacheMap->DirtyPages == 0)) {
1955 
1956  //
1957  // Move to the dirty list.
1958  //
1959 
1960  RemoveEntryList( &SharedCacheMap->SharedCacheMapLinks );
1961  InsertTailList( &CcDirtySharedCacheMapList.SharedCacheMapLinks,
1962  &SharedCacheMap->SharedCacheMapLinks );
1963 
1964  //
1965  // Make sure the Lazy Writer will wake up, because we
1966  // want him to delete this SharedCacheMap.
1967  //
1968 
1969  LazyWriter.OtherWork = TRUE;
1970  if (!LazyWriter.ScanActive) {
1971  CcScheduleLazyWriteScan( FALSE );
1972  }
1973  }
1974 
1975  CcReleaseMasterLock( OldIrql );
1976  }
1977 
1978  DebugTrace(-1, me, "CcPerformReadAhead -> VOID\n", 0 );
1979 
1980  return;
1981 }

1983 
1984 PBITMAP_RANGE
1985 CcFindBitmapRangeToDirty (
1986  IN PMBCB Mbcb,
1987  IN LONGLONG Page,
1988  IN PULONG *FreePageForSetting
1989  )
1990 
1991 /*++
1992 
1993 Routine Description:
1994 
1995  This routine looks for the bitmap range containing the specified page.
1996  If it is found it is returned so the caller can set some dirty bits.
1997  If it is not found, then an attempt is made to come up with a free range
1998  and set it up to describe the desired range. To come up with a free range,
1999  first we attempt to recycle the lowest range that does not currently contain
2000  any dirty pages. If there is no such range, then we allocate one.
2001 
2002 Arguments:
2003 
2004  Mbcb - Supplies the Mbcb in which to find the range.
2005 
2006  Page - Supplies the page number for the first page to be set dirty.
2007 
2008  FreePageForSetting - Supplies a free bitmap page of zeros from the zone; the
2009  caller's pointer is cleared on return if this page is used.
2010 
2011 Return Value:
2012 
2013  The desired bitmap range, or NULL if one could not be allocated.
2014 
2015 Environment:
2016 
2017  The BcbSpinLock must be held on entry.
2018 
2019 --*/
2020 
2021 {
2022  PBITMAP_RANGE BitmapRange, FreeRange;
2023  PLIST_ENTRY InsertPoint;
2024  LONGLONG BasePage;
2025 
2026  //
2027  // Initialize FreeRange and InsertPoint for the case we have
2028  // to initialize a range.
2029  //
2030 
2031  FreeRange = NULL;
2032  InsertPoint = &Mbcb->BitmapRanges;
2033 
2034  //
2035  // Point to the first bitmap range.
2036  //
2037 
2038  BitmapRange = (PBITMAP_RANGE)InsertPoint->Flink;
2039 
2040  //
2041  // Calculate the desired BasePage from the caller's page.
2042  //
2043 
2044  BasePage = (Page & ~(LONGLONG)((MBCB_BITMAP_BLOCK_SIZE * 8) - 1));
2045 
2046  //
2047  // Loop through the list until we find the range or we have a free range
2048  // and correct insertion point.
2049  //
2050 
2051  do {
2052 
2053  //
2054  // If we get an exact match, then we must have hit a fully-initialized
2055  // range which we can return.
2056  //
2057 
2058  if (BasePage == BitmapRange->BasePage) {
2059  return BitmapRange;
2060 
2061  //
2062  // Otherwise, see if the range is free and we have not captured a
2063  // free range yet.
2064  //
2065 
2066  } else if ((BitmapRange->DirtyPages == 0) && (FreeRange == NULL)) {
2067  FreeRange = BitmapRange;
2068 
2069  //
2070  // If we did not capture a free range, see if we need to update our
2071  // insertion point.
2072  //
2073 
2074  } else if (BasePage > BitmapRange->BasePage) {
2075  InsertPoint = &BitmapRange->Links;
2076  }
2077 
2078  //
2079  // Advance to the next range (or possibly back to the listhead).
2080  //
2081 
2082  BitmapRange = (PBITMAP_RANGE)BitmapRange->Links.Flink;
2083 
2084  //
2085  // Loop until we hit the end, or we know we are done updating both InsertPoint
2086  // and FreeRange.
2087  //
2088 
2089  } while ((BitmapRange != (PBITMAP_RANGE)&Mbcb->BitmapRanges) &&
2090  ((BasePage >= BitmapRange->BasePage) ||
2091  (FreeRange == NULL)));
2092 
2093  //
2094  // If we found a FreeRange we can use, then remove it from the list.
2095  //
2096 
2097  if (FreeRange != NULL) {
2098  RemoveEntryList( &FreeRange->Links );
2099 
2100  //
2101  // Otherwise we have to allocate the small bitmap range structure. We usually
2102  // try to avoid calling the pool package while owning a spin lock, but note the
2103  // following things which must be true if we hit this point:
2104  //
2105  // The file is larger than 3 bitmap ranges (normally 384MB on Intel).
2106  // Three ranges plus all previously allocated ranges are simultaneously dirty.
2107  //
2108  // The second point is fairly unlikely, especially for a sequential writer. It
2109  // can occur for a random writer in a large file, but eventually we will allocate
2110  // enough ranges to always describe how many ranges he can keep dirty at once!
2111  //
2112 
2113  } else {
2114  FreeRange = ExAllocatePoolWithTag( NonPagedPool, sizeof(BITMAP_RANGE), 'rBcC' );
2115  if (FreeRange == NULL) {
2116  return NULL;
2117  }
2118  RtlZeroMemory( FreeRange, sizeof(BITMAP_RANGE) );
2119  }
2120 
2121  //
2122  // Insert and initialize.
2123  //
2124 
2125  InsertHeadList( InsertPoint, &FreeRange->Links );
2126  FreeRange->BasePage = BasePage;
2127  FreeRange->FirstDirtyPage = MAXULONG;
2128  FreeRange->LastDirtyPage = 0;
2129 
2130  //
2131  // If the range does not have a bitmap yet, then consume the one we were passed
2132  // in.
2133  //
2134 
2135  if (FreeRange->Bitmap == NULL) {
2136  ASSERT(*FreePageForSetting != NULL);
2137  FreeRange->Bitmap = *FreePageForSetting;
2138  *FreePageForSetting = NULL;
2139  }
2140 
2141  return FreeRange;
2142 }
2143 
2144 
2145 PBITMAP_RANGE
2146 CcFindBitmapRangeToClean (
2147  IN PMBCB Mbcb,
2148  IN LONGLONG Page
2149  )
2150 
2151 /*++
2152 
2153 Routine Description:
2154 
2155  This routine starts from the specified page, and looks for a range with dirty
2156  pages. The caller must guarantee that some range exists with dirty pages. If
2157  the end of the ranges is hit before finding any dirty ranges, then this routine
2158  loops back to the start of the range list.
2159 
2160 Arguments:
2161 
2162  Mbcb - Supplies the Mbcb in which to find the range.
2163 
2164  Page - Supplies the page number for the first page to scan from.
2165 
2166 Return Value:
2167 
2168  The desired bitmap range with dirty pages.
2169 
2170 Environment:
2171 
2172  The BcbSpinLock must be held on entry.
2173 
2174 --*/
2175 
2176 {
2177  PBITMAP_RANGE BitmapRange;
2178 
2179  //
2180  // Point to the first bitmap range.
2181  //
2182 
2183  BitmapRange = (PBITMAP_RANGE)Mbcb->BitmapRanges.Flink;
2184 
2185  //
2186  // Loop through the list until we find the range to return.
2187  //
2188 
2189  do {
2190 
2191  //
2192  // If we hit the listhead, then wrap to find the first dirty range.
2193  //
2194 
2195  if (BitmapRange == (PBITMAP_RANGE)&Mbcb->BitmapRanges) {
2196 
2197  //
2198  // If Page is already 0, we are in an infinite loop.
2199  //
2200 
2201  ASSERT(Page != 0);
2202 
2203  //
2204  // Clear Page and fall through to advance to first range.
2205  //
2206 
2207  Page = 0;
2208 
2209 
2210  //
2211  // Otherwise, if we are in range, return the first range
2212  // with dirty pages.
2213  //
2214 
2215  } else if ((Page <= (BitmapRange->BasePage + BitmapRange->LastDirtyPage)) &&
2216  (BitmapRange->DirtyPages != 0)) {
2217  return BitmapRange;
2218  }
2219 
2220  //
2221  // Advance to the next range (or possibly back to the listhead).
2222  //
2223 
2224  BitmapRange = (PBITMAP_RANGE)BitmapRange->Links.Flink;
2225 
2226  } while (TRUE);
2227 }

2229 
2230 VOID
2231 CcSetDirtyInMask (
2232  IN PSHARED_CACHE_MAP SharedCacheMap,
2233  IN PLARGE_INTEGER FileOffset,
2234  IN ULONG Length
2235  )
2236 
2237 /*++
2238 
2239 Routine Description:
2240 
2241  This routine may be called to set a range of pages dirty in a user data
2242  file, by just setting the corresponding bits in the mask bcb.
2243 
2244  IMPORTANT NOTE:
2245 
2246  If this routine fails to set any bits due to an allocation failure,
2247  it just returns quietly without informing the caller. (Note that this
2248  routine is never called for no modified write sections.) The reason
2249  for this behavior is that this routine is sometimes called as part of
2250  error recovery (CcFreeActiveVacb, CcMdlWriteComplete, etc.) when it is
2251  essential to just keep on moving. Note that if an allocation failure does
2252  occur, this only means that MM will have to flush the modified page in
2253  time, since the Lazy Writer will not do it.
2254 
2255 Arguments:
2256 
2257  SharedCacheMap - SharedCacheMap where the pages are to be set dirty.
2258 
2259  FileOffset - FileOffset of first page to set dirty
2260 
2261  Length - Used in conjunction with FileOffset to determine how many pages
2262  to set dirty.
2263 
2264 Return Value:
2265 
2266  None
2267 
2268 --*/
2269 
2270 {
2271  KLOCK_QUEUE_HANDLE LockHandle;
2272  PMBCB Mbcb;
2273  PBITMAP_RANGE BitmapRange;
2274  LONGLONG FirstPage;
2275  LONGLONG LastPage;
2276  PULONG MaskPtr;
2277  ULONG Mask = 0;
2278  PULONG Bitmap = NULL;
2279 
2280  //
2281  // We assume no caller can cross a bitmap range boundary (currently not even
2282  // a view boundary!), so we do not want to loop through bitmap ranges.
2283  //
2284 
2285  ASSERT((FileOffset->QuadPart / MBCB_BITMAP_RANGE) ==
2286  ((FileOffset->QuadPart + Length - 1) / MBCB_BITMAP_RANGE));
2287 
2288  //
2289  // Initialize our locals.
2290  //
2291 
2292  FirstPage = FileOffset->QuadPart >> PAGE_SHIFT;
2293  LastPage = ((FileOffset->QuadPart + Length - 1) >> PAGE_SHIFT);
2294 
2295  //
2296  // PREfix correctly notes that Mbcb grande promotion test and the one
2297  // that decides to preallocate the bitmap buffer ever disagree, we will
2298  // be able to have a NULL Bitmap and die. This will not happen since we
2299  // guarantee that section size >= filesize. Assert this case, and we will
2300  // also assert that Bitmap is never NULL when needed - this should convince
2301  // PREfix we're OK.
2302  //
2303 
2304  ASSERT( (SharedCacheMap->SectionSize.QuadPart / PAGE_SIZE) > LastPage );
2305 
2306  //
2307  // If we have to convert to an Mbcb grande, we will loop back here to
2308  // preallocate another buffer.
2309  //
2310 
2311  do {
2312 
2313  //
2314  // For large streams, we need to preallocate a block we use for
2315  // we use for bitmaps. We allocate one, then loop back in the rare
2316  // case where we will need another. We free it at the bottom if we
2317  // don't need one.
2318  //
2319 
2320  if (SharedCacheMap->SectionSize.QuadPart > (MBCB_BITMAP_INITIAL_SIZE * 8 * PAGE_SIZE)) {
2321

2333  }

2337  //

2343  //

2397  //

2411  RtlZeroMemory( Mbcb->BitmapRange1.Bitmap, MBCB_BITMAP_INITIAL_SIZE );
2412  }

2415  // Store the new bitmap pointer and show we have consumed this one.
2416  //

2418  Mbcb->BitmapRange1.Bitmap = Bitmap;
2419  Bitmap = NULL;
2420 
2421  //
2422  // Insert and initialize the first range.
2423  //
2424 
2425  InsertTailList( &Mbcb->BitmapRanges, &Mbcb->BitmapRange2.Links );
2426  Mbcb->BitmapRange2.BasePage = MAXLONGLONG;
2427  Mbcb->BitmapRange2.FirstDirtyPage = MAXULONG;

2429  Mbcb->BitmapRange3.BasePage = MAXLONGLONG;
2430  Mbcb->BitmapRange3.FirstDirtyPage = MAXULONG;

2435  // to preallocate another buffer for CcFindBitmapRangeToDirty.
2436  //
2437 
2438  KeReleaseInStackQueuedSpinLock( &LockHandle );

2440  }

2444  //
2445

2447 
2448  //
2449  // If we could not allocate this dinky structure, break out quietly.
2450  //
2451 
2452  if (BitmapRange == NULL) {
2453  break;
2454  }
2455

2457  // Now update the first and last dirty page indices and the bitmap.
2458  //
2459 
2460  if (FirstPage < (BitmapRange->BasePage + BitmapRange->FirstDirtyPage)) {
2461  BitmapRange->FirstDirtyPage = (ULONG)(FirstPage - BitmapRange->BasePage);
2462  }
2463 
2464  if (LastPage > (BitmapRange->BasePage + BitmapRange->LastDirtyPage)) {
2465  BitmapRange->LastDirtyPage = (ULONG)(LastPage - BitmapRange->BasePage);
2466  }

2470  // may be changing lists.
2471  //
2472

2474

2476  // If this is the first dirty page for this cache map, there is some work
2477  // to do.
2478  //
2479 
2480  if (SharedCacheMap->DirtyPages == 0) {
2481 
2482  //
2483  // If the lazy write scan is not active, then start it.
2484  //
2485 
2486  if (!LazyWriter.ScanActive) {
2487  CcScheduleLazyWriteScan( FALSE );
2488  }
2489 
2490  //
2491  // Move to the dirty list.
2492  //

2496  &SharedCacheMap->SharedCacheMapLinks );
2497 
2498  Mbcb->ResumeWritePage = FirstPage;
2499  }

2502  Mask = 1 << ((ULONG)FirstPage % 32);
2503

2505  // Loop to set all of the bits and adjust the DirtyPage totals.
2506  //
2507 
2508  for ( ; FirstPage <= LastPage; FirstPage++) {
2509 
2510  if ((*MaskPtr & Mask) == 0) {
2511  CcChargeMaskDirtyPages( SharedCacheMap, Mbcb, BitmapRange, 1 );
2512  *MaskPtr |= Mask;
2513  }
2514 
2515  Mask <<= 1;
2516 
2517  if (Mask == 0) {
2518 
2519  MaskPtr += 1;
2520  Mask = 1;
2521  }
2522  }
2523 
2524  //
2525  // See if we need to advance our goal for ValidDataLength.
2526  //
2527 
2528  LastPage = FileOffset->QuadPart + Length;
2529 
2530  if (LastPage > SharedCacheMap->ValidDataGoal.QuadPart) {
2531  SharedCacheMap->ValidDataGoal.QuadPart = (LONGLONG)LastPage;
2532  }
2533 
2534  CcReleaseMasterLockFromDpcLevel();
2535 
2536  //
2537  // Continue until we have actually set the bits (there is a continue
2538  // which just wants to loop back and allocate another buffer).
2539  //
2540 
2541  } while (Mask == 0);
2542 
2543  //
2544  // Now if we preallocated a bitmap buffer, free it on the way out.
2545  //
2546 
2547  if (Bitmap != NULL) {
2548  CcAcquireVacbLockAtDpcLevel();
2549  CcDeallocateVacbLevel( (PVACB *)Bitmap, FALSE );
2550  CcReleaseVacbLockFromDpcLevel();
2551  }
2552  KeReleaseInStackQueuedSpinLock( &LockHandle );
2553 }

2556 VOID

2559  __in_opt PLARGE_INTEGER Lsn

2561 
2562 /*++
2563

2565 
2566  This routine may be called to set a Bcb (returned by CcPinFileData)
2567  dirty, and a candidate for the Lazy Writer. All Bcbs should be set
2568  dirty by calling this routine, even if they are to be flushed

2572

2575

2579 
2580  None
2581

2585  PBCB Bcbs[2];
2586  PBCB *BcbPtrPtr;
2587  KLOCK_QUEUE_HANDLE LockHandle;
2588  PSHARED_CACHE_MAP SharedCacheMap;
2589

2591 
2592  //
2593  // Assume this is a normal Bcb, and set up for loop below.
2594  //
2595 
2596  Bcbs[0] = (PBCB)BcbVoid;
2597  Bcbs[1] = NULL;
2598  BcbPtrPtr = &Bcbs[0];
2599 
2600  //
2601  // If it is an overlap Bcb, then point into the Bcb vector
2602  // for the loop.
2603  //
2604 
2605  if (Bcbs[0]->NodeTypeCode == CACHE_NTC_OBCB) {
2606  BcbPtrPtr = &((POBCB)Bcbs[0])->Bcbs[0];
2607  }
2608 
2609  //

2611  //
2612

2614 
2615  Bcbs[0] = *(BcbPtrPtr++);
2616 
2617  //
2618  // Should be no ReadOnly Bcbs
2619  //
2620

2626  // We have to acquire the shared cache map list, because we
2627  // may be changing lists.
2628  //
2629 
2630  KeAcquireInStackQueuedSpinLock( &SharedCacheMap->BcbSpinLock, &LockHandle );
2631 
2632  if (!Bcbs[0]->Dirty) {
2633 
2634  ULONG Pages = Bcbs[0]->ByteLength >> PAGE_SHIFT;
2635 
2636  //

2638  // it is set Undirty, and assign the next modification time stamp.
2639  //
2640 
2641  Bcbs[0]->Dirty = TRUE;
2642

2649  Bcbs[0]->NewestLsn = *Lsn;

2655  //

2657  //
2658 
2659  CcAcquireMasterLockAtDpcLevel();
2660  if ((SharedCacheMap->DirtyPages == 0) &&
2661  !FlagOn(SharedCacheMap->Flags, DISABLE_WRITE_BEHIND)) {
2662 
2663  //
2664  // If the lazy write scan is not active, then start it.
2665  //
2666 
2667  if (!LazyWriter.ScanActive) {
2668  CcScheduleLazyWriteScan( FALSE );
2669  }
2670 
2671  RemoveEntryList( &SharedCacheMap->SharedCacheMapLinks );
2672  InsertTailList( &CcDirtySharedCacheMapList.SharedCacheMapLinks,
2673  &SharedCacheMap->SharedCacheMapLinks );
2674  }
2675 
2676  CcChargePinDirtyPages( SharedCacheMap, Pages );
2677  CcReleaseMasterLockFromDpcLevel();
2678  }
2679

2681  // If this Lsn happens to be older/newer than the ones we have stored, then

2683  //
2684

2686

2688  Bcbs[0]->OldestLsn = *Lsn;
2689  }
2690 
2691  if (Lsn->QuadPart > Bcbs[0]->NewestLsn.QuadPart) {
2692  Bcbs[0]->NewestLsn = *Lsn;
2693  }
2694  }
2695 
2696  //
2697  // See if we need to advance our goal for ValidDataLength.
2698  //
2699 
2700  if ( Bcbs[0]->BeyondLastByte.QuadPart > SharedCacheMap->ValidDataGoal.QuadPart ) {
2701 
2702  SharedCacheMap->ValidDataGoal = Bcbs[0]->BeyondLastByte;
2703  }
2704 
2705  KeReleaseInStackQueuedSpinLock( &LockHandle );
2706  }
2707 
2708  DebugTrace(-1, me, "CcSetDirtyPinnedData -> VOID\n", 0 );
2709 }

2712 NTSTATUS
2713 CcSetValidData (

2715  IN PLARGE_INTEGER ValidDataLength
2716  )
2717 
2718 /*++
2719 
2720 Routine Description:
2721 
2722  This routine is used to call the File System to update ValidDataLength
2723  for a file.
2724 
2725 Arguments:
2726 
2727  FileObject - A pointer to a referenced file object describing which file
2728  the read should be performed from.
2729 
2730  ValidDataLength - Pointer to new ValidDataLength.
2731

2733 
2734  Status of operation.
2735 
2736 --*/

2738 {
2739  PIO_STACK_LOCATION IrpSp;
2740  PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject;
2741  NTSTATUS Status;
2742  FILE_END_OF_FILE_INFORMATION Buffer;
2743  IO_STATUS_BLOCK IoStatus;
2744  KEVENT Event;
2745  PIRP Irp;
2746 
2747  DebugTrace(+1, me, "CcSetValidData:\n", 0 );

2773  //

2779

2788

2814  IrpSp->Parameters.SetFile.AdvanceOnly = TRUE;

2820

2826  //
2827

2852 //
2853 // Internal Support Routine
2854 //
2855 
2856 BOOLEAN
2857 CcAcquireByteRangeForWrite (
2858  IN PSHARED_CACHE_MAP SharedCacheMap,
2859  IN PLARGE_INTEGER TargetOffset OPTIONAL,
2860  IN ULONG TargetLength,
2861  OUT PLARGE_INTEGER FileOffset,
2862  OUT PULONG Length,
2863  OUT PBCB *FirstBcb
2864  )
2865 
2866 /*++
2867 
2868 Routine Description:
2869 
2870  This routine is called by the Lazy Writer to try to find a contiguous
2871  range of bytes from the specified SharedCacheMap that are dirty and
2872  should be flushed. After flushing, these bytes should be released
2873  by calling CcReleaseByteRangeFromWrite.
2874 
2875  Dirty ranges are returned in strictly increasing order.
2876 
2877 Arguments:
2878 
2879  SharedCacheMap - for the file for which the dirty byte range is sought
2880 
2881  TargetOffset - If specified, then only the specified range is
2882  to be flushed.
2883 
2884  TargetLength - If target offset specified, this completes the range.
2885  In any case, this field is zero for the Lazy Writer,
2886  and nonzero for explicit flush calls.
2887 
2888  FileOffset - Returns the offset for the beginning of the dirty byte
2889  range to flush
2890 
2891  Length - Returns the length of bytes in the range.
2892 
2893  FirstBcb - Returns the first Bcb in the list for the range, to be used
2894  when calling CcReleaseByteRangeFromWrite, or NULL if dirty
2895  pages were found in the mask Bcb.
2896 
2897 Return Value:
2898 
2899  FALSE - if no dirty byte range could be found to match the necessary
2900  criteria.
2901 
2902  TRUE - if a dirty byte range is being returned.
2903 
2904 --*/
2905 
2906 {
2907  KLOCK_QUEUE_HANDLE LockHandle;
2908  PMBCB Mbcb;
2909  PBCB Bcb;
2910  LARGE_INTEGER LsnToFlushTo = {0, 0};
2911 
2912  LOGICAL BcbLookasideCheck = FALSE;
2913 
2914  PBITMAP_RANGE BitmapRange;
2915  PULONG EndPtr;
2916  PULONG MaskPtr;
2917  ULONG Mask;
2918  LONGLONG FirstDirtyPage;
2919  ULONG OriginalFirstDirtyPage;
2920  LONGLONG LastDirtyPage = MAXLONGLONG;
2921 
2922  DebugTrace(+1, me, "CcAcquireByteRangeForWrite:\n", 0);
2923  DebugTrace( 0, me, " SharedCacheMap = %08lx\n", SharedCacheMap);
2924 
2925  //
2926  // Initially clear outputs.
2927  //
2928 
2929  FileOffset->QuadPart = 0;
2930  *Length = 0;
2931 
2932  //
2933  // We must acquire the SharedCacheMap->BcbSpinLock.
2934  //
2935 
2936  KeAcquireInStackQueuedSpinLock( &SharedCacheMap->BcbSpinLock, &LockHandle );
2937 
2938  //
2939  // See if there is a simple Mask Bcb, and if there is anything dirty in
2940  // it. If so we will simply handle that case here by processing the bitmap.
2941  //
2942 
2943  Mbcb = SharedCacheMap->Mbcb;
2944 
2945  if ((Mbcb != NULL) &&
2946  (Mbcb->DirtyPages != 0) &&
2947  ((Mbcb->PagesToWrite != 0) || (TargetLength != 0))) {
2948 
2949  //
2950  // If a target range was specified (outside call to CcFlush for a range),
2951  // then calculate FirstPage and EndPtr based on these inputs.
2952  //
2953 
2954  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT(TargetOffset)) {
2955 
2956  FirstDirtyPage = TargetOffset->QuadPart >> PAGE_SHIFT;
2957  LastDirtyPage = (TargetOffset->QuadPart + TargetLength - 1) >> PAGE_SHIFT;
2958 
2959  //
2960  // Find the bitmap range containing the first dirty page.
2961  //
2962 
2963  BitmapRange = CcFindBitmapRangeToClean( Mbcb, FirstDirtyPage );
2964 
2965  //
2966  // If the target range is not dirty, get out. We may have even
2967  // gotten back a nonoverlapping bitmap range.
2968  //
2969 
2970  if ((LastDirtyPage < (BitmapRange->BasePage + BitmapRange->FirstDirtyPage)) ||
2971  (FirstDirtyPage > (BitmapRange->BasePage + BitmapRange->LastDirtyPage))) {
2972 
2973  goto Scan_Bcbs;
2974  }
2975 
2976  if (LastDirtyPage < (BitmapRange->BasePage + BitmapRange->LastDirtyPage)) {
2977  EndPtr = &BitmapRange->Bitmap[(ULONG)(LastDirtyPage - BitmapRange->BasePage) / 32];
2978  } else {
2979  EndPtr = &BitmapRange->Bitmap[BitmapRange->LastDirtyPage / 32];
2980  }
2981 
2982 
2983  //
2984  // Otherwise, for the Lazy Writer pick up where we left off.
2985  //
2986 
2987  } else {
2988 
2989  //
2990  // If a length was specified, then it is an explicit flush, and
2991  // we want to start with the first dirty page, else the Lazy Writer
2992  // starts from the ResumeWritePage.
2993  //
2994 
2995  FirstDirtyPage = 0;
2996  if (TargetLength == 0) {
2997  FirstDirtyPage = Mbcb->ResumeWritePage;
2998  }
2999 
3000  //
3001  // Now find the next (cyclic) dirty page from this point.
3002  //
3003 
3004  BitmapRange = CcFindBitmapRangeToClean( Mbcb, FirstDirtyPage );
3005 
3006  //
3007  // If the page we thought we were looking for is beyond the last dirty page
3008  // of this range, then CcFindBitmapRangeToClean must have wrapped back to
3009  // the start of the file, and we should resume on the first dirty page of
3010  // this range.
3011  //
3012 
3013  if (FirstDirtyPage > (BitmapRange->BasePage + BitmapRange->LastDirtyPage)) {
3014  FirstDirtyPage = BitmapRange->BasePage + BitmapRange->FirstDirtyPage;
3015  }
3016 
3017  EndPtr = &BitmapRange->Bitmap[BitmapRange->LastDirtyPage / 32];
3018  }
3019 
3020  //
3021  // Now we can skip over any clean pages.
3022  //
3023 
3024  if (FirstDirtyPage < (BitmapRange->BasePage + BitmapRange->FirstDirtyPage)) {
3025  FirstDirtyPage = BitmapRange->BasePage + BitmapRange->FirstDirtyPage;
3026  }
3027 
3028  //
3029  // Form a few other inputs for our dirty page scan.
3030  //
3031 
3032  MaskPtr = &BitmapRange->Bitmap[(ULONG)(FirstDirtyPage - BitmapRange->BasePage) / 32];
3033  Mask = (ULONG)(-1 << (FirstDirtyPage % 32));
3034  OriginalFirstDirtyPage = (ULONG)(FirstDirtyPage - BitmapRange->BasePage);
3035 
3036  //
3037  // Because of the possibility of getting stuck on a "hot spot" which gets
3038  // modified over and over, we want to be very careful to resume exactly
3039  // at the recorded resume point. If there is nothing there, then we
3040  // fall into the loop below to scan for nozero long words in the bitmap,
3041  // starting at the next longword.
3042  //

3772  Length - As returned from CcAcquirebyteRangeForWrite
3773 
3774  FirstBcb - As returned from CcAcquireByteRangeForWrite
3775 
3776  VerifyRequired - supplied as TRUE if a verify required error was received.
3777  In this case we must mark/leave the data dirty so that
3778  we will try to write it again.
3779 
3780 Return Value:
3781 
3782  None
3783 
3784 --*/
3785 
3786 {
3787  LARGE_INTEGER LastOffset;
3788  PBCB NextBcb;
3789 
3790  DebugTrace(+1, me, "CcReleaseByteRangeFromWrite:\n", 0);
3791  DebugTrace2(0, me, " FileOffset = %08lx, %08lx\n", FileOffset->LowPart,
3792  FileOffset->HighPart );
3793 
3794  //
3795  // If it is a mask Mbcb we are getting, then we only have to check
3796  // for VerifyRequired.
3797  //
3798 
3799  if (FirstBcb == NULL) {
3800 
3801  ASSERT(Length != 0);
3802 
3803  if (VerifyRequired) {
3804  CcSetDirtyInMask( SharedCacheMap, FileOffset, Length );
3805  }
3806 
3807  DebugTrace(-1, me, "CcReleaseByteRangeFromWrite -> VOID\n", 0);
3808 
3809  return;
3810  }
3811 
3812  //
3813  // PREfix correctly notes that if the caller gives us a listhead to start with,
3814  // we will not have filled in LastOffset by the time we do our first loop test.
3815  // For PREfix's benefit (and ours), assert we really are starting with a Bcb.
3816  //
3817 
3818  ASSERT( FirstBcb->NodeTypeCode == CACHE_NTC_BCB );
3819 
3820  //
3821  // Now loop to free up all of the Bcbs. If modified writing is disabled
3822  // for each Bcb, then we are to set it clean here, since we are synchronized
3823  // with callers who set the data dirty. Otherwise we only have the Bcb pinned
3824  // so it will not go away, and we only unpin it here.
3825  //
3826 
3827  do {
3828  NextBcb = CONTAINING_RECORD( FirstBcb->BcbLinks.Flink, BCB, BcbLinks );
3829 
3830  //
3831  // Skip over any listheads.
3832  //
3833 
3834  if (FirstBcb->NodeTypeCode == CACHE_NTC_BCB) {
3835 
3836  LastOffset = FirstBcb->FileOffset;
3837 
3838  //
3839  // If this is file system metadata (we disabled modified writing),
3840  // then this is the time to mark the buffer clean, so long as we
3841  // did not get verify required.
3842  //
3843 
3844  if (FlagOn(SharedCacheMap->Flags, MODIFIED_WRITE_DISABLED)) {
3845 
3846  CcUnpinFileData( FirstBcb,
3847  BooleanFlagOn(SharedCacheMap->Flags, DISABLE_WRITE_BEHIND),
3848  SET_CLEAN );
3849  }
3850 
3851  //
3852  // If we got verify required, we have to mark the buffer dirty again
3853  // so we will try again later. Note we have to make this call again
3854  // to make sure the right thing happens with time stamps.
3855  //
3856 
3857  if (VerifyRequired) {
3858  CcSetDirtyPinnedData( FirstBcb, NULL );
3859  }
3860 
3861  //
3862  // Finally remove a pin count left over from CcAcquireByteRangeForWrite.
3863  //
3864 
3865  CcUnpinFileDataReleaseFromFlush( FirstBcb, TRUE, UNPIN );
3866  }
3867 
3868  FirstBcb = NextBcb;
3869  } while (FileOffset->QuadPart != LastOffset.QuadPart);
3870 
3871  DebugTrace(-1, me, "CcReleaseByteRangeFromWrite -> VOID\n", 0);
3872 }
