3874 
3875 //
3876 // Internal Support Routine
3877 //
3878 
3879 VOID
3880 FASTCALL
3881 CcWriteBehind (
3882  IN PSHARED_CACHE_MAP SharedCacheMap,
3883  IN PIO_STATUS_BLOCK IoStatus
3884  )
3885 
3886 /*++
3887 
3888 Routine Description:
3889 
3890  This routine may be called with Wait = FALSE to see if write behind
3891  is required, or with Wait = TRUE to perform write behind as required.
3892 
3893  The code is very similar to the the code that the Lazy Writer performs
3894  for each SharedCacheMap. The main difference is in the call to
3895  CcAcquireByteRangeForWrite. Write Behind does not care about time
3896  stamps (passing ULONG to accept all time stamps), but it will never
3897  dump the first (highest byte offset) buffer in the list if the last
3898  byte of that buffer is not yet written. The Lazy Writer does exactly
3899  the opposite, in the sense that it is totally time-driven, and will
3900  even dump a partially modified buffer if it sits around long enough.
3901 
3902 Arguments:
3903 
3904  SharedCacheMap - Pointer to SharedCacheMap to be written
3905 
3906 Return Value:
3907 
3908  FALSE - if write behind is required, but the caller supplied
3909  Wait = FALSE
3910 
3911  TRUE - if write behind is complete or not required
3912 
3913 --*/
3914 
3915 {
3916  KLOCK_QUEUE_HANDLE LockHandle;
3917  ULONG ActivePage;
3918  ULONG PageIsDirty;
3919  PMBCB Mbcb;
3920  NTSTATUS Status;
3921  PVACB ActiveVacb = NULL;
3922  LOGICAL FlushFailed = FALSE;
3923 
3924  DebugTrace(+1, me, "CcWriteBehind\n", 0 );
3925  DebugTrace( 0, me, " SharedCacheMap = %08lx\n", SharedCacheMap );
3926 
3927  //
3928  // First we have to acquire the file for LazyWrite, to avoid
3929  // deadlocking with writers to the file. We do this via the
3930  // CallBack procedure specified to CcInitializeCacheMap.
3931  //
3932 
3933  if (!(*SharedCacheMap->Callbacks->AcquireForLazyWrite)
3934  ( SharedCacheMap->LazyWriteContext, TRUE )) {
3935 
3936  //
3937  // The filesystem is hinting that it doesn't think that it can
3938  // service the write without significant delay so we will defer
3939  // and come back later. Simply drop the queued flag ... note that
3940  // we do not modify CcPagesYetToWrite, in the hope that we can make
3941  // up the difference in some other cache map on this pass.
3942  //
3943 
3944  CcAcquireMasterLock( &LockHandle.OldIrql );
3945  ClearFlag(SharedCacheMap->Flags, WRITE_QUEUED);
3946  CcReleaseMasterLock( LockHandle.OldIrql );
3947 
3948  IoStatus->Status = STATUS_FILE_LOCK_CONFLICT;
3949  return;
3950  }
3951 
3952  //
3953  // See if there is a previous active page to clean up, but only
3954  // do so now if it is the last dirty page or no users have the
3955  // file open. We will free it below after dropping the spinlock.
3956  //
3957 
3958  KeAcquireInStackQueuedSpinLock( &SharedCacheMap->BcbSpinLock, &LockHandle );
3959  CcAcquireMasterLockAtDpcLevel();
3960 
3961  if ((SharedCacheMap->DirtyPages <= 1) || (SharedCacheMap->OpenCount == 0)) {
3962  GetActiveVacbAtDpcLevel( SharedCacheMap, ActiveVacb, ActivePage, PageIsDirty );
3963  }
3964 
3965  //
3966  // Increment open count so that our caller's views stay available
3967  // for CcGetVacbMiss. We could be tying up all of the views, and
3968  // still need to write file sizes.
3969  //
3970 
3971  CcIncrementOpenCount( SharedCacheMap, 'brWS' );
3972 
3973  //
3974  // If there is a mask bcb, then we need to establish a target for
3975  // it to flush.
3976  //
3977 
3978  if ((Mbcb = SharedCacheMap->Mbcb) != 0) {
3979 
3980  //
3981  // Set a target of pages to write, assuming that any Active
3982  // Vacb will increase the number.
3983  //
3984 
3985  Mbcb->PagesToWrite = Mbcb->DirtyPages + ((ActiveVacb != NULL) ? 1 : 0);
3986 
3987  if (Mbcb->PagesToWrite > CcPagesYetToWrite) {
3988 
3989  Mbcb->PagesToWrite = CcPagesYetToWrite;
3990  }
3991  }
3992 
3993  CcReleaseMasterLockFromDpcLevel();
3994  KeReleaseInStackQueuedSpinLock( &LockHandle );
3995 
3996  //
3997  // Now free the active Vacb, if we found one.
3998  //
3999 
4000  if (ActiveVacb != NULL) {
4001 
4002  CcFreeActiveVacb( SharedCacheMap, ActiveVacb, ActivePage, PageIsDirty );
4003  }
4004 
4005  //
4006  // Now perform the lazy writing for this file via a special call
4007  // to CcFlushCache. He recognizes us by the &CcNoDelay input to
4008  // FileOffset, which signifies a Lazy Write, but is subsequently
4009  // ignored.
4010  //
4011 
4012  CcFlushCache( SharedCacheMap->FileObject->SectionObjectPointer,
4013  &CcNoDelay,
4014  1,
4015  IoStatus );
4016 
4017  //
4018  // No need for the Lazy Write resource now.
4019  //
4020 
4021  (*SharedCacheMap->Callbacks->ReleaseFromLazyWrite)
4022  ( SharedCacheMap->LazyWriteContext );
4023 
4024  //
4025  // If we are supposed to do a fast lazy write on this shared cache map,
4026  // we need to remember if the flush failed so that we can signal Mm when
4027  // we acquire the master lock below. We will signal Mm if we failed for
4028  // any reason other than STATUS_VERIFY_REQUIRED, including
4029  // STATUS_FILE_LOCK_CONFLICT.
4030  //
4031 
4032  if (!NT_SUCCESS( IoStatus->Status ) && (IoStatus->Status != STATUS_VERIFY_REQUIRED)) {
4033 
4034  FlushFailed = TRUE;
4035  }
4036 
4037  //
4038  // Check if we need to put up a popup.
4039  //
4040 
4041  if (!NT_SUCCESS(IoStatus->Status) && !RetryError(IoStatus->Status)) {
4042 
4043  //
4044  // We lost writebehind data. Bemoan our fate into the system event
4045  // log and throw a popup with a meaningful name to the desktop.
4046  //
4047 
4048  POBJECT_NAME_INFORMATION FileNameInfo = NULL;
4049  NTSTATUS Status;
4050 
4051  //
4052  // Increment the count of how many of these we've had. This counter
4053  // is useful in attempting to discriminate some corruption cases under
4054  // test.
4055  //
4056 
4057  CcLostDelayedWrites += 1;
4058 
4059  Status = IoQueryFileDosDeviceName( SharedCacheMap->FileObject, &FileNameInfo );
4060 
4061  if ( Status == STATUS_SUCCESS ) {
4062  IoRaiseInformationalHardError( STATUS_LOST_WRITEBEHIND_DATA, &FileNameInfo->Name, NULL );
4063 
4064  } else {
4065  if ( SharedCacheMap->FileObject->FileName.Length &&
4066  SharedCacheMap->FileObject->FileName.MaximumLength &&
4067  SharedCacheMap->FileObject->FileName.Buffer ) {
4068 
4069  IoRaiseInformationalHardError( STATUS_LOST_WRITEBEHIND_DATA, &SharedCacheMap->FileObject->FileName, NULL );
4070  }
4071  }
4072 
4073  CcLogError( SharedCacheMap->FileObject,
4074  ( Status == STATUS_SUCCESS ?
4075  &FileNameInfo->Name :
4076  &SharedCacheMap->FileObject->FileName ),
4077  IO_LOST_DELAYED_WRITE,
4078  IoStatus->Status,
4079  IRP_MJ_WRITE );
4080 
4081  if (FileNameInfo) {
4082  ExFreePool(FileNameInfo);
4083  }
4084 
4085  //
4086  // See if there is any deferred writes we can post.
4087  //
4088 
4089  } else if (!IsListEmpty(&CcDeferredWrites)) {
4090  CcPostDeferredWrites();
4091  }
4092 
4093  //
4094  // Now acquire BcbSpinLock again to check for ValidData updates.
4095  //
4096 
4097  KeAcquireInStackQueuedSpinLock( &SharedCacheMap->BcbSpinLock, &LockHandle );
4098 
4099  //
4100  // If the the current ValidDataGoal is greater (or equal) than ValidDataLength,
4101  // then we must see if we have advanced beyond the current ValidDataLength.
4102  //
4103  // If we have NEVER written anything out from this shared cache map, then
4104  // there is no need to check anything associated with valid data length
4105  // here. We will come by here again when, and if, anybody actually
4106  // modifies the file and we lazy write some data.
4107  //
4108 
4109  Status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
4110  if (FlagOn(SharedCacheMap->Flags, (LAZY_WRITE_OCCURRED | FORCED_WRITE_THROUGH)) &&
4111  (SharedCacheMap->ValidDataGoal.QuadPart >= SharedCacheMap->ValidDataLength.QuadPart) &&
4112  (SharedCacheMap->ValidDataLength.QuadPart != MAXLONGLONG) &&
4113  (SharedCacheMap->FileSize.QuadPart != 0)) {
4114 
4115  LARGE_INTEGER NewValidDataLength;
4116 
4117  NewValidDataLength = CcGetFlushedValidData( SharedCacheMap->FileObject->SectionObjectPointer,
4118  TRUE );
4119 
4120  //
4121  // If New ValidDataLength has been written, then we have to
4122  // call the file system back to update it. We must temporarily
4123  // drop our global list while we do this, which is safe to do since
4124  // we have not cleared WRITE_QUEUED.
4125  //
4126  // Note we keep calling any time we wrote the last page of the file,
4127  // to solve the "famous" AFS Server problem. The file system will
4128  // truncate our valid data call to whatever is currently valid. But
4129  // then if he writes a little more, we do not want to stop calling
4130  // back.
4131  //
4132 
4133  if ( NewValidDataLength.QuadPart >= SharedCacheMap->ValidDataLength.QuadPart ) {
4134 
4135  KeReleaseInStackQueuedSpinLock( &LockHandle );
4136 
4137  //
4138  // Call file system to set new valid data. We have no
4139  // one to tell if this doesn't work.
4140  //
4141 
4142  Status = CcSetValidData( SharedCacheMap->FileObject,
4143  &NewValidDataLength );
4144 
4145  KeAcquireInStackQueuedSpinLock( &SharedCacheMap->BcbSpinLock, &LockHandle );
4146  if (NT_SUCCESS(Status)) {
4147  SharedCacheMap->ValidDataLength = NewValidDataLength;
4148  }
4149  }
4150  }
4151 
4152  KeReleaseInStackQueuedSpinLock( &LockHandle );
4153 
4154  //
4155  // Show we are done.
4156  //
4157 
4158  CcAcquireMasterLock( &LockHandle.OldIrql );
4159  CcDecrementOpenCount( SharedCacheMap, 'brWF' );
4160 
4161  //
4162  // Check to see if this is a shared cache map Mm is waiting to be torn
4163  // down and if this flush failed. If so, we need to signal Mm because
4164  // this cache map will not be able to be torn down quickly.
4165  //
4166 
4167  if (FlushFailed && FlagOn( SharedCacheMap->Flags, WAITING_FOR_TEARDOWN )) {
4168 
4169  CcCancelMmWaitForUninitializeCacheMap( SharedCacheMap );
4170  }
4171 
4172  //
4173  // Make an approximate guess about whether we will call CcDeleteSharedCacheMap or not
4174  // to truncate the file.
4175  //
4176  // Also do not delete the SharedCacheMap if we got an error on the ValidDataLength
4177  // callback. If we get a resource allocation failure or a retryable error (due to
4178  // log file full?), we have no one to tell, so we must just loop back and try again.
4179  // Of course all I/O errors are just too bad.
4180  //
4181 
4182  if (SharedCacheMap->OpenCount == 0) {
4183 
4184 
4185  if (NT_SUCCESS(Status) ||
4186  ((Status != STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES) && !RetryError(Status))) {
4187 
4188  CcReleaseMasterLock( LockHandle.OldIrql );
4189  FsRtlAcquireFileExclusive( SharedCacheMap->FileObject );
4190  CcAcquireMasterLock( &LockHandle.OldIrql );
4191 
4192  //
4193  // Now really see if we are to delete this SharedCacheMap. By having released
4194  // first we avoid a deadlock with the file system when the FileObject is
4195  // dereferenced. Note that CcDeleteSharedCacheMap requires that the
4196  // CcMasterSpinLock already be acquired, and it releases it.
4197  //
4198  // Note that we must retest since we dropped and reacquired the master
4199  // lock.
4200  //
4201 
4202  if ((SharedCacheMap->OpenCount == 0)
4203 
4204  &&
4205 
4206  ( (SharedCacheMap->DirtyPages == 0)
4207 
4208  ||
4209 
4210  ( (SharedCacheMap->FileSize.QuadPart == 0) &&
4211  !FlagOn(SharedCacheMap->Flags, PIN_ACCESS) ) )
4212  ) {
4213 
4214  //
4215  // Make sure to drop the requeue flag in case the write hit the timeout at
4216  // the same time it finished everything up.
4217  //
4218 
4219  CcDeleteSharedCacheMap( SharedCacheMap, LockHandle.OldIrql, TRUE );
4220  IoStatus->Information = 0;
4221  SharedCacheMap = NULL;
4222 
4223  } else {
4224 
4225  CcReleaseMasterLock( LockHandle.OldIrql );
4226  FsRtlReleaseFile( SharedCacheMap->FileObject );
4227  CcAcquireMasterLock( &LockHandle.OldIrql );
4228  }
4229 
4230  } else {
4231 
4232  //
4233  // We got an error where we should retry our operation. Move this
4234  // shared cache map back to the dirty list if it is not already
4235  // there.
4236  //
4237 
4238  if (SharedCacheMap->DirtyPages == 0) {
4239 
4240  RemoveEntryList( &SharedCacheMap->SharedCacheMapLinks );
4241  InsertTailList( &CcDirtySharedCacheMapList.SharedCacheMapLinks,
4242  &SharedCacheMap->SharedCacheMapLinks );
4243 
4244  //
4245  // Make sure the Lazy Writer will wake up, because we
4246  // want him to delete this SharedCacheMap.
4247  //
4248 
4249  LazyWriter.OtherWork = TRUE;
4250  if (!LazyWriter.ScanActive) {
4251  CcScheduleLazyWriteScan( FALSE );
4252  }
4253  }
4254  }
4255  }
4256 
4257  //
4258  // In the normal case, we just clear the flag on the way out if
4259  // we will not requeue the workitem.
4260  //
4261 
4262  if (SharedCacheMap != NULL) {
4263 
4264  if (IoStatus->Information != CC_REQUEUE) {
4265  ClearFlag(SharedCacheMap->Flags, WRITE_QUEUED);
4266  }
4267  CcReleaseMasterLock( LockHandle.OldIrql );
4268  }
4269 
4270  DebugTrace(-1, me, "CcWriteBehind->VOID\n", 0 );
4271 
4272  return;
4273 }

4275 
4276 LARGE_INTEGER
4277 CcGetFlushedValidData (
4278  __in PSECTION_OBJECT_POINTERS SectionObjectPointer,
4279  __in BOOLEAN CcInternalCaller
4280  )
4281 
4282 /*++
4283 
4284 Routine Description:
4285 
4286  This routine may be called by a file system to find out how far the Cache Manager
4287  has flushed in the stream. More accurately, this routine returns either the FileOffset
4288  of the lowest dirty page currently in the file.
4289 
4290  NOTE that even though the routine takes SectionObjectPointer, the caller must ensure
4291  that the stream is cached and stays cached for the duration of this routine, much like
4292  for the copy routines, etc.
4293 
4294 Arguments:
4295 
4296  SectionObjectPointer - A pointer to the Section Object Pointers
4297  structure in the nonpaged Fcb.
4298 
4299  CcInternalCaller - must be TRUE if the caller is coming from Cc, FALSE otherwise.
4300  TRUE implies the need for self-synchronization.
4301 
4302 Return Value:
4303 
4304  The derived number for flushed ValidData, or MAXLONGLONG in the quad part if
4305  the Section is not cached. (Naturally the caller can guarantee that this case
4306  does not occur, and internal callers do.)
4307 
4308 --*/
4309 
4310 {
4311  PSHARED_CACHE_MAP SharedCacheMap;
4312  KLOCK_QUEUE_HANDLE LockHandle;
4313  LARGE_INTEGER NewValidDataLength;
4314 
4315  //
4316  // External callers may be unsynchronized with this shared cache map
4317  // perhaps going away underneath this call.
4318  //
4319 
4320  if (!CcInternalCaller) {
4321 
4322  CcAcquireMasterLock( &LockHandle.OldIrql );
4323 
4324  SharedCacheMap = SectionObjectPointer->SharedCacheMap;
4325 
4326  if (SharedCacheMap == NULL) {
4327  CcReleaseMasterLock( LockHandle.OldIrql );
4328  NewValidDataLength.QuadPart = MAXLONGLONG;
4329  return NewValidDataLength;
4330  }
4331 
4332  CcIncrementOpenCount( SharedCacheMap, 'dfGS' );
4333  CcReleaseMasterLock( LockHandle.OldIrql );
4334  KeAcquireInStackQueuedSpinLock( &SharedCacheMap->BcbSpinLock, &LockHandle );
4335 
4336  } else {
4337 
4338  SharedCacheMap = SectionObjectPointer->SharedCacheMap;
4339  }
4340 
4341  ASSERT( SharedCacheMap != NULL );
4342 
4343  //
4344  // If the file is entirely clean, then we wish to return
4345  // the new ValidDataLength as equal to ValidDataGoal.
4346  //
4347 
4348  NewValidDataLength = SharedCacheMap->ValidDataGoal;
4349 
4350  //
4351  // If there may be dirty pages we will look at the last Bcb in the
4352  // descending-order Bcb list, and see if it describes data beyond
4353  // ValidDataGoal.
4354  //
4355  // It is important to note that since we use DirtyPages as a faux
4356  // reference count over some short windows (+1, -1) the simple
4357  // fact it is nonzero does *not* mean the file is dirty.
4358  //
4359  // (This test is logically too conservative. For example, the last Bcb
4360  // may not even be dirty (in which case we should look at its
4361  // predecessor), or we may have earlier written valid data to this
4362  // byte range (which also means if we knew this we could look at
4363  // the predecessor). This simply means that the Lazy Writer may not
4364  // successfully get ValidDataLength updated in a file being randomly
4365  // accessed until the level of file access dies down, or at the latest
4366  // until the file is closed. However, security will never be
4367  // compromised.)
4368  //
4369 
4370  if (SharedCacheMap->DirtyPages) {
4371 
4372  PBITMAP_RANGE BitmapRange;
4373  PBCB LastBcb;
4374  PMBCB Mbcb = SharedCacheMap->Mbcb;
4375 
4376  if ((Mbcb != NULL) && (Mbcb->DirtyPages != 0)) {
4377 
4378  BitmapRange = CcFindBitmapRangeToClean( Mbcb, 0 );
4379 
4380  ASSERT(BitmapRange->FirstDirtyPage != MAXULONG);
4381 
4382  NewValidDataLength.QuadPart = (BitmapRange->BasePage + BitmapRange->FirstDirtyPage)
4383  << PAGE_SHIFT;
4384  }
4385 
4386  LastBcb = CONTAINING_RECORD( SharedCacheMap->BcbList.Flink,
4387  BCB,
4388  BcbLinks );
4389 
4390  while (&LastBcb->BcbLinks != &SharedCacheMap->BcbList) {
4391 
4392  if ((LastBcb->NodeTypeCode == CACHE_NTC_BCB) && LastBcb->Dirty) {
4393  break;
4394  }
4395 
4396  LastBcb = CONTAINING_RECORD( LastBcb->BcbLinks.Flink,
4397  BCB,
4398  BcbLinks );
4399  }
4400 
4401  //
4402  // Check the Base of the last entry.
4403  //
4404 
4405  if ((&LastBcb->BcbLinks != &SharedCacheMap->BcbList) &&
4406  (LastBcb->FileOffset.QuadPart < NewValidDataLength.QuadPart )) {
4407 
4408  NewValidDataLength = LastBcb->FileOffset;
4409  }
4410  }
4411 
4412  if (!CcInternalCaller) {
4413 
4414  //
4415  // Remove our reference.
4416  //
4417 
4418  CcAcquireMasterLockAtDpcLevel();
4419  CcDecrementOpenCount( SharedCacheMap, 'dfGF' );
4420 
4421  if ((SharedCacheMap->OpenCount == 0) &&
4422  !FlagOn(SharedCacheMap->Flags, WRITE_QUEUED) &&
4423  (SharedCacheMap->DirtyPages == 0)) {
4424 
4425  //
4426  // Move to the dirty list.
4427  //
4428 
4429  RemoveEntryList( &SharedCacheMap->SharedCacheMapLinks );
4430  InsertTailList( &CcDirtySharedCacheMapList.SharedCacheMapLinks,
4431  &SharedCacheMap->SharedCacheMapLinks );
4432 
4433  //
4434  // Make sure the Lazy Writer will wake up, because we
4435  // want him to delete this SharedCacheMap.
4436  //
4437 
4438  LazyWriter.OtherWork = TRUE;
4439  if (!LazyWriter.ScanActive) {
4440  CcScheduleLazyWriteScan( FALSE );
4441  }
4442  }
4443 
4444  KeReleaseInStackQueuedSpinLockFromDpcLevel( &LockHandle );
4445  CcReleaseMasterLock( LockHandle.OldIrql );
4446  }
4447 
4448  return NewValidDataLength;
4449 }

4456  __in ULONG Length,
4457  __out_opt PIO_STATUS_BLOCK IoStatus
4458  )
4459 
4460 /*++
4461 
4462 Routine Description:
4463 
4464  This routine may be called to flush dirty data from the cache to the
4465  cached file on disk. Any byte range within the file may be flushed,
4466  or the entire file may be flushed by omitting the FileOffset parameter.
4467 
4468  This routine does not take a Wait parameter; the caller should assume
4469  that it will always block.
4470 
4471 Arguments:
4472 
4473  SectionObjectPointer - A pointer to the Section Object Pointers
4474  structure in the nonpaged Fcb.
4475 
4476  FileOffset - If this parameter is supplied (not NULL), then only the
4477  byte range specified by FileOffset and Length are flushed.
4478  If &CcNoDelay is specified, then this signifies the call
4479  from the Lazy Writer, and the lazy write scan should resume
4480  as normal from the last spot where it left off in the file.
4481 
4482  Length - Defines the length of the byte range to flush, starting at
4483  FileOffset. This parameter is ignored if FileOffset is
4484  specified as NULL.
4485 
4486  IoStatus - The I/O status resulting from the flush operation.
4487 
4488 Return Value:
4489 
4490  None.
4491 
4492 --*/

4516 
4517  DebugTrace(+1, me, "CcFlushCache:\n", 0 );
4518  DebugTrace( 0, mm, " SectionObjectPointer = %08lx\n", SectionObjectPointer );
4519  DebugTrace2(0, me, " FileOffset = %08lx, %08lx\n",
4520  ARGUMENT_PRESENT(FileOffset) ? FileOffset->LowPart
4521  : 0,
4522  ARGUMENT_PRESENT(FileOffset) ? FileOffset->HighPart
4523  : 0 );

4527  // If IoStatus passed a Null pointer, set up to through status away.
4528  //
4529

4531  IoStatus = &TrashStatus;
4532  }

4538  // routine, which is also a public routine callable by file systems,
4539  // the Lazy Writer shows his call by specifying CcNoDelay as the file offset!
4540  //
4541  // Also, in case we do not write anything because we see only HotSpot(s),

4545  //

4549  IsLazyWriter = TRUE;
4550  FileOffset = NULL;
4551  SetFlag( MmFlushFlags, MM_FLUSH_FAIL_COLLISIONS );
4552 
4553  } else {
4554

4556  }
4557 
4558  CcAcquireMasterLock( &OldIrql );
4559

4561 
4562  //
4563  // Awareness is indicated by the lowbit of the FileOffset pointer.
4564  // Non-awareness of a private write stream results in a no-op.
4565  //
4566 
4567  if (SharedCacheMap != NULL) {
4568 
4569  if (IsLazyWriter && FlagOn( SharedCacheMap->Flags, WAITING_FOR_TEARDOWN )) {
4570 
4571  //
4572  // If the WAITING_FOR_TEARDOWN flag is set, Mm is waiting for Cc
4573  // to flush this file and teardown the shared cache map so that
4574  // the file can be remapped as a section image. In this case,
4575  // we want the lazy writer to flush all dirty data for this file
4576  // to disk now, not just a fraction of the dirty pages to keep
4577  // within the lazy write threshold.
4578  //

4581

4584  // of a flush collision, so we will clear that MmFlushFlag now.
4585  //
4586 
4587  ClearFlag( MmFlushFlags, MM_FLUSH_FAIL_COLLISIONS );
4588  }

4590  if (FlagOn( SharedCacheMap->Flags, PRIVATE_WRITE )) {
4591 
4592  if (((ULONG_PTR)FileOffset & 1) == 0) {
4593 
4594  CcReleaseMasterLock( OldIrql );
4595  return;
4596 
4597  }
4598

4600  }
4601 
4602  //
4603  // If this file is targeted to a CD ROM device, we don't want to
4604  // deal back off when we collide with the mapped page writer because
4605  // we could colliding in the window between the point where Mm has
4606  // marked the pages "WriteInProgress" but is waiting to acquire the
4607  // file system locks. Often, these file systems will fail the
4608  // AcquireForModWrite if the file does not have any user mapped views
4609  // so that the flushes come in sequential order, which it is very
4610  // important for efficient writing on these devices.
4611  //
4612

4614  (SharedCacheMap->FileObject->DeviceObject->DeviceType == FILE_DEVICE_CD_ROM)) {
4615 
4616  ClearFlag( MmFlushFlags, MM_FLUSH_FAIL_COLLISIONS );
4617  }
4618  }

4620  //
4621  // If there is nothing to do, return here.
4622  //
4623 
4624  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT(FileOffset) && (Length == 0)) {
4625 
4626  CcReleaseMasterLock( OldIrql );
4627  DebugTrace(-1, me, "CcFlushCache -> VOID\n", 0 );
4628  return;
4629  }
4630 
4631  //
4632  // See if the file is cached.
4633  //
4634 
4635  if (SharedCacheMap != NULL) {
4636 
4637  //
4638  // Increment the open count to keep it from going away.
4639  //
4640 
4641  CcIncrementOpenCount( SharedCacheMap, 'fcCS' );

4644 
4645  ULONG FirstPage = 0;
4646  ULONG LastPage = MAXULONG;
4647 
4648  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT(FileOffset)) {
4649 
4650  FirstPage = (ULONG)(FileOffset->QuadPart >> PAGE_SHIFT);
4651  LastPage = (ULONG)((FileOffset->QuadPart + Length - 1) >> PAGE_SHIFT);
4652  }
4653 
4654  //
4655  // Make sure we do not flush the active page without zeroing any
4656  // uninitialized data. Also, it is very important to free the active
4657  // page if it is the one to be flushed, so that we get the dirty
4658  // bit out to the Pfn.
4659  //
4660 
4661  if (((((LONGLONG)LastPage + 1) << PAGE_SHIFT) > SharedCacheMap->ValidDataGoal.QuadPart) ||
4662 
4663  ((SharedCacheMap->NeedToZero != NULL) &&
4664  (FirstPage <= SharedCacheMap->NeedToZeroPage) &&
4665  (LastPage >= SharedCacheMap->NeedToZeroPage)) ||
4666 
4667  ((SharedCacheMap->ActiveVacb != NULL) &&
4668  (FirstPage <= SharedCacheMap->ActivePage) &&
4669  (LastPage >= SharedCacheMap->ActivePage))) {
4670 
4671  GetActiveVacbAtDpcLevel( SharedCacheMap, ActiveVacb, RemainingLength, TempLength );
4672  FreeActiveVacb = TRUE;
4673  }
4674  }
4675  }
4676 
4677  CcReleaseMasterLock( OldIrql );
4678 
4679  if (FreeActiveVacb) {
4680  CcFreeActiveVacb( SharedCacheMap, ActiveVacb, RemainingLength, TempLength );
4681  }
4682 
4683  //
4684  // If there is a user-mapped file, then we perform the "service" of
4685  // flushing even data not written via the file system. Note that this
4686  // is pretty important for folks provoking the flush/purge of a coherency
4687  // operation.
4688  //
4689  // It is critical this happen before we examine our own hints. In the course
4690  // of this flush it is possible valid data length will be advanced by the
4691  // underlying filesystem, with CcZero'ing behind - which will cause us to
4692  // make some dirty zeroes in the cache.
4693  //
4694  // If this stream allows mapping for overwrite, we also need to flush the
4695  // full range now since there could be dirty data in this range that Cc
4696  // isn't tracking.
4697  //
4698 
4699  if (((SharedCacheMap == NULL)
4700  ||
4701  FlagOn(((PFSRTL_COMMON_FCB_HEADER)(SharedCacheMap->FileObject->FsContext))->Flags,
4702  FSRTL_FLAG_USER_MAPPED_FILE)
4703  ||
4704  FlagOn(SharedCacheMap->Flags, CALLER_TRACKS_DIRTY_DATA))
4705  &&
4706  !IsLazyWriter) {
4707 
4708  //
4709  // Call MM to flush the section through our view.
4710  //
4711 
4712  DebugTrace( 0, mm, "MmFlushSection:\n", 0 );
4713  DebugTrace( 0, mm, " SectionObjectPointer = %08lx\n", SectionObjectPointer );
4714  DebugTrace2(0, me, " FileOffset = %08lx, %08lx\n",
4715  ARGUMENT_PRESENT(FileOffset) ? FileOffset->LowPart
4716  : 0,
4717  ARGUMENT_PRESENT(FileOffset) ? FileOffset->HighPart
4718  : 0 );
4719  DebugTrace( 0, mm, " RegionSize = %08lx\n", Length );

4722  // In this case, we always want to acquire the file instead of using
4723  // the flags we have setup MmFlushFlags. To avoid cache coherency
4724  // issues, we want to do our best to make sure this flush is completed
4725  // successfully before continuing.
4726  //
4727 
4728  Status = MmFlushSection( SectionObjectPointer,
4729  FileOffset,
4730  Length,
4731  IoStatus,
4732  MM_FLUSH_ACQUIRE_FILE );
4733 
4734  ASSERT( IoStatus->Status != STATUS_ENCOUNTERED_WRITE_IN_PROGRESS );
4735 
4736  if ((!NT_SUCCESS(IoStatus->Status)) && !RetryError(IoStatus->Status)) {
4737 
4738  PopupRequired = TRUE;
4739  PopupStatus = IoStatus->Status;
4740  }
4741 
4742  DebugTrace2(0, mm, " <IoStatus = %08lx, %08lx\n",
4743  IoStatus->Status, IoStatus->Information );
4744  }

4747  // Scan for dirty pages if there is a shared cache map.
4748  //
4749 
4750  if (SharedCacheMap != NULL) {
4751 
4752  //
4753  // If FileOffset was not specified then set to flush entire region
4754  // and set valid data length to the goal so that we will not get
4755  // any more call backs.
4756  //
4757  // NOTE: We could be flushing the entire file if this is
4758  // a FastLazyWrite (if FastLazyWrite is TRUE, IsLazyWriter will also
4759  // always be TRUE). In this case we do NOT want to do this
4760  // optimization to move VDL to VDG *before* we've done the flush
4761  // because it is not safe to update the SharedCacheMap's VDL at this
4762  // time -- the lazy write path only has the file acquired shared, not
4763  // exclusive as is the case when the user has requested the file to
4764  // be flushed.
4765 
4766  if (!IsLazyWriter && !ARGUMENT_PRESENT(FileOffset)) {
4767 
4768  SharedCacheMap->ValidDataLength = SharedCacheMap->ValidDataGoal;
4769  }
4770 
4771  //
4772  // If this is an explicit flush, initialize our offset to scan for.
4773  //
4774 
4775  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT(FileOffset)) {
4776  TargetOffset = *FileOffset;
4777  }
4778 
4779  //
4780  // Assume we want to pass the explicit flush flag in Length.
4781  // But overwrite it if a length really was specified. On
4782  // subsequent loops, NextLength will have some nonzero value.
4783  //
4784 
4785  NextLength = 1;
4786  if (Length != 0) {
4787  NextLength = Length;
4788  }
4789 
4790  //
4791  // Now calculate the tick that will signal the expiration of a
4792  // lazy writer tick interval.
4793  //
4794 
4795  if (IsLazyWriter) {
4796 
4797  KeQueryTickCount( &EndTick );
4798  EndTick.QuadPart += CcIdleDelayTick;
4799  }
4800

4802  // Loop as long as we find buffers to flush for this
4803  // SharedCacheMap, and we are not trying to delete the guy.
4804  //
4805 
4806  while (((SharedCacheMap->PagesToWrite != 0) || !(IsLazyWriter && !FastLazyWrite))
4807 
4808  &&
4809  ((SharedCacheMap->FileSize.QuadPart != 0) ||
4810  FlagOn(SharedCacheMap->Flags, PIN_ACCESS))
4811 
4812  &&
4813 
4814  !VerifyRequired
4815 
4816  &&
4817 
4818  CcAcquireByteRangeForWrite ( SharedCacheMap,
4819  (IsLazyWriter && !FastLazyWrite ) ? NULL : (ARGUMENT_PRESENT(FileOffset) ?
4820  &TargetOffset : NULL),
4821  (IsLazyWriter && !FastLazyWrite ) ? 0: NextLength,
4822  &NextFileOffset,
4823  &NextLength,
4824  &FirstBcb )) {
4825 
4826  //
4827  // Assume this range is not a hot spot or a collided flush.
4828  //
4829 
4830  HotSpot = FALSE;
4831  CollidedFlush = FALSE;
4832 
4833  //
4834  // We defer calling Mm to set address range modified until here, to take
4835  // overhead out of the main line path, and to reduce the number of TBIS
4836  // on a multiprocessor.
4837  //
4838 
4839  RemainingLength = NextLength;
4840 
4841  do {
4842 
4843  //
4844  // See if the next file offset is mapped. (If not, the dirty bit
4845  // was propagated on the unmap.)
4846  //
4847 
4848  if ((TempVa = CcGetVirtualAddressIfMapped( SharedCacheMap,
4849  NextFileOffset.QuadPart + NextLength - RemainingLength,
4850  &ActiveVacb,
4851  &TempLength)) != NULL) {
4852 
4853  //
4854  // Reduce TempLength to RemainingLength if necessary, and
4855  // call MM.
4856  //
4857 
4858  if (TempLength > RemainingLength) {
4859  TempLength = RemainingLength;
4860  }
4861 
4862  //
4863  // Clear the Dirty bit (if set) in the PTE and set the
4864  // Pfn modified. Assume if the Pte was dirty, that this may
4865  // be a hot spot. Do not do hot spots for metadata, and unless
4866  // they are within ValidDataLength as reported to the file system
4867  // via CcSetValidData.
4868  //
4869 
4870  HotSpot = (BOOLEAN)(((MmSetAddressRangeModified(TempVa, TempLength) || HotSpot) &&
4871  ((NextFileOffset.QuadPart + NextLength) <
4872  (SharedCacheMap->ValidDataLength.QuadPart)) &&
4873  ((SharedCacheMap->LazyWritePassCount & 0xF) != 0) &&
4874  (IsLazyWriter && !FastLazyWrite)) &&
4875  !FlagOn(SharedCacheMap->Flags, MODIFIED_WRITE_DISABLED));
4876 
4877  CcFreeVirtualAddress( ActiveVacb );
4878 
4879  } else {
4880 
4881  //
4882  // Reduce TempLength to RemainingLength if necessary.
4883  //
4884 
4885  if (TempLength > RemainingLength) {
4886  TempLength = RemainingLength;
4887  }
4888  }
4889 
4890  //
4891  // Reduce RemainingLength by what we processed.
4892  //
4893 
4894  RemainingLength -= TempLength;
4895 
4896  //
4897  // Loop until done.
4898  //
4899 
4900  } while (RemainingLength != 0);
4901 
4902  CcLazyWriteHotSpots += HotSpot;
4903 
4904  //
4905  // Now flush, now flush if we do not think it is a hot spot.
4906  //
4907 
4908  if (!HotSpot) {
4909 
4910  MmFlushSection( SharedCacheMap->FileObject->SectionObjectPointer,
4911  &NextFileOffset,
4912  NextLength,
4913  IoStatus,
4914  MmFlushFlags );
4915 
4916  if (NT_SUCCESS(IoStatus->Status)) {
4917 
4918  if (!FlagOn(SharedCacheMap->Flags, LAZY_WRITE_OCCURRED)) {
4919 
4920  CcAcquireMasterLock( &OldIrql );
4921  SetFlag(SharedCacheMap->Flags, LAZY_WRITE_OCCURRED);
4922  CcReleaseMasterLock( OldIrql );
4923  }
4924 
4925  //
4926  // Increment performance counters
4927  //
4928 
4929  if (IsLazyWriter) {
4930 
4931  CcLazyWriteIos += 1;
4932  CcLazyWritePages += (NextLength + PAGE_SIZE - 1) >> PAGE_SHIFT;
4933  }
4934 
4935  } else {
4936 
4937  LARGE_INTEGER Offset = NextFileOffset;
4938  ULONG RetryLength = NextLength;
4939 
4940  DebugTrace2( 0, 0, "I/O Error on Cache Flush: %08lx, %08lx\n",
4941  IoStatus->Status, IoStatus->Information );
4942 
4943  //
4944  // If we collided with mapped page writer, we don't
4945  // want to terminate this flush loop yet. We do want
4946  // to track the collision so that we re-mark the pages
4947  // dirty, but then we want to continue the loop and
4948  // try to flush the next range of dirty data since it
4949  // is unlikely we will collide again.
4950  //
4951 
4952  if (IoStatus->Status == STATUS_ENCOUNTERED_WRITE_IN_PROGRESS) {
4953 
4954 
4955  CollidedFlush = TRUE;
4956 
4957  //
4958  // If we get any other RetryError, we set VerifyRequired so
4959  // that we will re-mark the pages as dirty then terminate
4960  // this flush loop.
4961  //
4962 
4963  } else if (RetryError(IoStatus->Status)) {
4964 
4965  VerifyRequired = TRUE;
4966 
4967  //
4968  // Loop to write each page individually, starting with one
4969  // more try on the page that got the error, in case that page
4970  // or any page beyond it can be successfully written
4971  // individually. Note that Offset and RetryLength are
4972  // guaranteed to be in integral pages, but the Information
4973  // field from the failed request is not.
4974  //
4975  // We ignore errors now, and give it one last shot, before
4976  // setting the pages clean (see below).
4977  //
4978 
4979  } else {
4980 
4981  do {
4982 
4983  DebugTrace2( 0, 0, "Trying page at offset %08lx, %08lx\n",
4984  Offset.LowPart, Offset.HighPart );
4985 
4986  MmFlushSection ( SharedCacheMap->FileObject->SectionObjectPointer,
4987  &Offset,
4988  PAGE_SIZE,
4989  IoStatus,
4990  MmFlushFlags );
4991 
4992  DebugTrace2( 0, 0, "I/O status = %08lx, %08lx\n",
4993  IoStatus->Status, IoStatus->Information );
4994 
4995  if (NT_SUCCESS(IoStatus->Status)) {
4996  CcAcquireMasterLock( &OldIrql );
4997  SetFlag(SharedCacheMap->Flags, LAZY_WRITE_OCCURRED);
4998  CcReleaseMasterLock( OldIrql );
4999  }
5000 
5001  if ((!NT_SUCCESS(IoStatus->Status)) && !RetryError(IoStatus->Status)) {
5002 
5003  PopupRequired = TRUE;
5004  PopupStatus = IoStatus->Status;
5005  }
5006 
5007  VerifyRequired = VerifyRequired || RetryError(IoStatus->Status);
5008 
5009  Offset.QuadPart = Offset.QuadPart + (LONGLONG)PAGE_SIZE;
5010  RetryLength -= PAGE_SIZE;
5011 
5012  } while(RetryLength > 0);
5013  }
5014  }
5015  }
5016 
5017  //
5018  // Now release the Bcb resources and set them clean. Note we do not check
5019  // here for errors, and just returned in the I/O status. Errors on writes
5020  // are rare to begin with. Nonetheless, our strategy is to rely on
5021  // one or more of the following (depending on the file system) to prevent
5022  // errors from getting to us.
5023  //
5024  // - Retries and/or other forms of error recovery in the disk driver
5025  // - Mirroring driver
5026  // - Hot fixing in the noncached path of the file system
5027  //
5028  // In the unexpected case that a write error does get through, we
5029  // *currently* just set the Bcbs clean anyway, rather than let
5030  // Bcbs and pages accumulate which cannot be written. Note we did
5031  // a popup above to at least notify the guy.
5032  //
5033  // Set the pages dirty again if we either saw a HotSpot or got
5034  // verify required.
5035  //
5036 
5037  CcReleaseByteRangeFromWrite ( SharedCacheMap,
5038  &NextFileOffset,
5039  NextLength,
5040  FirstBcb,
5041  (BOOLEAN)(HotSpot || CollidedFlush || VerifyRequired) );
5042 
5043  //
5044  // See if there is any deferred writes we should post.
5045  //
5046 
5047  BytesWritten += NextLength;
5048  if ((BytesWritten >= 0x40000) && !IsListEmpty(&CcDeferredWrites)) {
5049  CcPostDeferredWrites();
5050  BytesWritten = 0;
5051  }
5052 
5053  //
5054  // If we're the lazy writer and have spent more than the active tick
5055  // length in this loop, break out for a requeue so we share the
5056  // file resources.
5057  //
5058 
5059  if (IsLazyWriter) {
5060 
5061  KeQueryTickCount( &CurrentTick );
5062 
5063  if (CurrentTick.QuadPart > EndTick.QuadPart) {
5064  IoStatus->Information = CC_REQUEUE;
5065  break;
5066  }
5067  }
5068 
5069  //
5070  // Now for explicit flushes, we should advance our range.
5071  //
5072 
5073  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT(FileOffset)) {
5074 
5075  NextFileOffset.QuadPart += NextLength;
5076 
5077  //
5078  // Done yet?
5079  //
5080 
5081  if ((FileOffset->QuadPart + Length) <= NextFileOffset.QuadPart) {
5082  break;
5083  }
5084 
5085  //
5086  // Calculate new target range
5087  //
5088 
5089  NextLength = (ULONG)((FileOffset->QuadPart + Length) - NextFileOffset.QuadPart);
5090  TargetOffset = NextFileOffset;
5091  }
5092  }
5093  }
5094 
5095  //
5096  // See if there are any deferred writes we should post if
5097  // we escaped the loop without checking after a series of
5098  // flushes.
5099  //
5100 
5101  if (BytesWritten != 0 && !IsListEmpty(&CcDeferredWrites)) {
5102 
5103  CcPostDeferredWrites();
5104  }
5105 
5106  //
5107  // Now we can get rid of the open count, and clean up as required.
5108  //
5109 
5110  if (SharedCacheMap != NULL) {
5111 
5112  //
5113  // Serialize again to decrement the open count.
5114  //
5115 
5116  CcAcquireMasterLock( &OldIrql );
5117 
5118  CcDecrementOpenCount( SharedCacheMap, 'fcCF' );
5119 
5120  if ((SharedCacheMap->OpenCount == 0) &&
5121  !FlagOn(SharedCacheMap->Flags, WRITE_QUEUED) &&
5122  (SharedCacheMap->DirtyPages == 0)) {
5123 
5124  //
5125  // Move to the dirty list.
5126  //
5127 
5128  RemoveEntryList( &SharedCacheMap->SharedCacheMapLinks );
5129  InsertTailList( &CcDirtySharedCacheMapList.SharedCacheMapLinks,
5130  &SharedCacheMap->SharedCacheMapLinks );
5131 
5132  //
5133  // Make sure the Lazy Writer will wake up, because we
5134  // want him to delete this SharedCacheMap.
5135  //
5136 
5137  LazyWriter.OtherWork = TRUE;
5138  if (!LazyWriter.ScanActive) {
5139  CcScheduleLazyWriteScan( FALSE );
5140  }
5141  }
5142 
5143  CcReleaseMasterLock( OldIrql );
5144  }
5145 
5146  //
5147  // Make sure and return the first error to our caller. In the
5148  // case of the Lazy Writer, a popup will be issued.
5149  //
5150 
5151  if (PopupRequired) {
5152  IoStatus->Status = PopupStatus;

5238 VOID
5239 CcRepinBcb (
5240  __in PVOID Bcb
5241  )
5242 
5243 /*++
5244 
5245 Routine Description:
5246 
5247  This routine may be called by a file system to pin a Bcb an additional
5248  time in order to reserve it for Write Through or error recovery.
5249  Typically the file system would do this the first time that it sets a
5250  pinned buffer dirty while processing a WriteThrough request, or any
5251  time that it determines that a buffer will be required for WriteThrough.
5252 
5253  The call to this routine must be followed by a call to CcUnpinRepinnedBcb.
5254  CcUnpinRepinnedBcb should normally be called during request completion
5255  after all other resources have been released. CcUnpinRepinnedBcb
5256  synchronously writes the buffer (for WriteThrough requests) and performs
5257  the matching unpin for this call.
5258 
5259 Arguments:
5260 
5261  Bcb - Supplies a pointer to a previously pinned Bcb
5262 
5263 Return Value:
5264 
5265  None.
5266 
5267 --*/
5268 
5269 {
5270  KLOCK_QUEUE_HANDLE LockHandle;
5271 
5272  KeAcquireInStackQueuedSpinLock( &((PBCB)Bcb)->SharedCacheMap->BcbSpinLock, &LockHandle );
5273 
5274  ((PBCB)Bcb)->PinCount += 1;
5275 
5276  KeReleaseInStackQueuedSpinLock( &LockHandle );
5277 }

5279 
5280 VOID
5281 CcUnpinRepinnedBcb (
5282  __in PVOID Bcb,
5283  __in BOOLEAN WriteThrough,
5284  __out PIO_STATUS_BLOCK IoStatus
5285  )
5286 
5287 /*++
5288 
5289 Routine Description:
5290 
5291  This routine may be called to Write a previously pinned buffer
5292  through to the file. It must have been preceded by a call to
5293  CcRepinBcb. As this routine must acquire the Bcb
5294  resource exclusive, the caller must be extremely careful to avoid
5295  deadlocks. Ideally the caller owns no resources at all when it
5296  calls this routine, or else the caller should guarantee that it
5297  has nothing else pinned in this same file. (The latter rule is
5298  the one used to avoid deadlocks in calls from CcCopyWrite and
5299  CcMdlWrite.)
5300 
5301 Arguments:
5302 
5303  Bcb - Pointer to a Bcb which was previously specified in a call
5304  to CcRepinBcb.
5305 
5306  WriteThrough - TRUE if the Bcb should be written through.
5307 
5308  IoStatus - Returns the I/O status for the operation.
5309 
5310 Return Value:
5311 
5312  None.
5313 
5314 --*/
5315 
5316 {
5317  PSHARED_CACHE_MAP SharedCacheMap = ((PBCB)Bcb)->SharedCacheMap;
5318 
5319  DebugTrace(+1, me, "CcUnpinRepinnedBcb\n", 0 );
5320  DebugTrace( 0, me, " Bcb = %08lx\n", Bcb );
5321  DebugTrace( 0, me, " WriteThrough = %02lx\n", WriteThrough );
5322 
5323  //
5324  // Set status to success for non write through case.
5325  //
5326 
5327  IoStatus->Status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
5328 
5329  if (WriteThrough) {
5330 
5331  //
5332  // Acquire Bcb exclusive to eliminate possible modifiers of the buffer,
5333  // since we are about to write its buffer.
5334  //
5335 
5336  if (FlagOn(SharedCacheMap->Flags, MODIFIED_WRITE_DISABLED)) {
5337  ExAcquireResourceExclusiveLite( &((PBCB)Bcb)->Resource, TRUE );
5338  }
5339 
5340  //
5341  // Now, there is a chance that the LazyWriter has already written
5342  // it, since the resource was free. We will only write it if it
5343  // is still dirty.
5344  //
5345 
5346  if (((PBCB)Bcb)->Dirty) {
5347 
5348  //
5349  // First we make sure that the dirty bit in the PFN database is set.
5350  //
5351 
5352  ASSERT( ((PBCB)Bcb)->BaseAddress != NULL );
5353  MmSetAddressRangeModified( ((PBCB)Bcb)->BaseAddress,
5354  ((PBCB)Bcb)->ByteLength );
5355 
5356  //
5357  // Now release the Bcb resource and set it clean. Note we do not check
5358  // here for errors, and just return the I/O status. Errors on writes
5359  // are rare to begin with. Nonetheless, our strategy is to rely on
5360  // one or more of the following (depending on the file system) to prevent
5361  // errors from getting to us.
5362  //
5363  // - Retries and/or other forms of error recovery in the disk driver
5364  // - Mirroring driver
5365  // - Hot fixing in the noncached path of the file system
5366  //
5367  // In the unexpected case that a write error does get through, we
5368  // report it to our caller, but go ahead and set the Bcb clean. There
5369  // seems to be no point in letting Bcbs (and pages in physical memory)
5370  // accumulate which can never go away because we get an unrecoverable I/O
5371  // error.
5372  //
5373 
5374  //
5375  // We specify TRUE here for ReadOnly so that we will keep the
5376  // resource during the flush.
5377  //
5378 
5379  CcUnpinFileData( (PBCB)Bcb, TRUE, SET_CLEAN );
5380 
5381  //
5382  // Write it out.
5383  //
5384 
5385  MmFlushSection( ((PBCB)Bcb)->SharedCacheMap->FileObject->SectionObjectPointer,
5386  &((PBCB)Bcb)->FileOffset,
5387  ((PBCB)Bcb)->ByteLength,
5388  IoStatus,
5389  MM_FLUSH_ACQUIRE_FILE );
5390 
5391  ASSERT( IoStatus->Status != STATUS_ENCOUNTERED_WRITE_IN_PROGRESS );
5392 
5393  //
5394  // If we got verify required, we have to mark the buffer dirty again
5395  // so we will try again later.
5396  //
5397 
5398  if (RetryError(IoStatus->Status)) {
5399  CcSetDirtyPinnedData( (PBCB)Bcb, NULL );
5400  }
5401 
5402  //
5403  // Now remove the final pin count now that we have set it clean.
5404  //
5405 
5406  CcUnpinFileData( (PBCB)Bcb, FALSE, UNPIN );
5407 
5408  //
5409  // See if there is any deferred writes we can post.
5410  //
5411 
5412  if (!IsListEmpty(&CcDeferredWrites)) {
5413  CcPostDeferredWrites();
5414  }
5415  }
5416  else {
5417 
5418  //
5419  // Lazy Writer got there first, just free the resource and unpin.
5420  //
5421 
5422  CcUnpinFileData( (PBCB)Bcb, FALSE, UNPIN );
5423 
5424  }
5425 
5426  DebugTrace2(0, me, " <IoStatus = %08lx, %08lx\n", IoStatus->Status,
5427  IoStatus->Information );
5428  }
5429 
5430  //
5431  // Non-WriteThrough case
5432  //
5433 
5434  else {
5435 
5436  CcUnpinFileData( (PBCB)Bcb, TRUE, UNPIN );
5437 
5438  //
5439  // Set status to success for non write through case.
5440  //
5441 
5442  IoStatus->Status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
5443  }
5444 
5445  DebugTrace(-1, me, "CcUnpinRepinnedBcb -> VOID\n", 0 );
5446 }

5449 //
5450 // Internal Support Routine
5451 //
5452 
5453 BOOLEAN
5454 CcFindBcb (
5455  IN PSHARED_CACHE_MAP SharedCacheMap,
5456  IN PLARGE_INTEGER FileOffset,
5457  IN OUT PLARGE_INTEGER BeyondLastByte,
5458  OUT PBCB *Bcb
5459  )
5460 
5461 /*++
5462 
5463 Routine Description:
5464 
5465  This routine is called to find a Bcb describing the specified byte range
5466  of a file. It returns TRUE if it could at least find a Bcb which describes
5467  the beginning of the specified byte range, or else FALSE if the first
5468  part of the byte range is not present. In the latter case, the requested
5469  byte range (TrialLength) is truncated if there is currently a Bcb which
5470  describes bytes beyond the beginning of the byte range.
5471 
5472  The caller may see if the entire byte range is being returned by examining
5473  the Bcb, and the caller (or caller's caller) may then make subsequent
5474  calls if the data is not all returned.
5475 
5476  The BcbSpinLock must be currently acquired.
5477 
5478 Arguments:
5479 
5480  SharedCacheMap - Supplies a pointer to the SharedCacheMap for the file
5481  in which the byte range is desired.
5482 
5483  FileOffset - Supplies the file offset for the beginning of the desired
5484  byte range.
5485 
5486  BeyondLastByte - Supplies the file offset of the ending of the desired
5487  byte range + 1. Note that this offset will be truncated
5488  on return if the Bcb was not found, but bytes beyond the
5489  beginning of the Bcb are contained in another Bcb.
5490 
5491  Bcb - returns a Bcb describing the beginning of the byte range if also
5492  returning TRUE, or else the point in the Bcb list to insert after.
5493 
5494 Return Value:
5495 
5496  FALSE - if no Bcb describes the beginning of the desired byte range
5497 
5498  TRUE - if a Bcb is being returned describing at least an initial
5499  part of the byte range.
5500 
5501 --*/
5502 
5503 {
5504  PLIST_ENTRY BcbList;
5505  PBCB Bcbt;
5506  BOOLEAN Found = FALSE;
5507 
5508  DebugTrace(+1, me, "CcFindBcb:\n", 0 );
5509  DebugTrace( 0, me, " SharedCacheMap = %08lx\n", SharedCacheMap );
5510  DebugTrace2(0, me, " FileOffset = %08lx, %08lx\n", FileOffset->LowPart,
5511  FileOffset->HighPart );
5512  DebugTrace2(0, me, " TrialLength = %08lx, %08lx\n", TrialLength->LowPart,
5513  TrialLength->HighPart );
5514 
5515  //
5516  // We want to terminate scans by testing the NodeTypeCode field from the
5517  // BcbLinks, so we want to see the SharedCacheMap signature from the same
5518  // offset.
5519  //
5520 
5521  ASSERT(FIELD_OFFSET(SHARED_CACHE_MAP, BcbList) == FIELD_OFFSET(BCB, BcbLinks));
5522 
5523  //
5524  // Similarly, when we hit one of the BcbListHeads in the array, small negative
5525  // offsets are all structure pointers, so we are counting on the Bcb signature
5526  // to have some non-Ulong address bits set.
5527  //
5528 
5529  ASSERT((CACHE_NTC_BCB & 3) != 0);
5530 
5531  //
5532  // Get address of Bcb listhead that is *after* the Bcb we are looking for,
5533  // for backwards scan. It is important that we fail in the forward
5534  // direction so that we are looking in the right segment of the Bcb list.
5535  //
5536 
5537  BcbList = CcGetBcbListHead( SharedCacheMap,
5538  FileOffset->QuadPart + SIZE_PER_BCB_LIST,
5539  TRUE );
5540 
5541  //
5542  // Search for an entry that overlaps the specified range, or until we hit
5543  // a listhead.
5544  //
5545 
5546  Bcbt = CONTAINING_RECORD(BcbList->Flink, BCB, BcbLinks);
5547 
5548  //
5549  // First see if we really have to do Large arithmetic or not, and
5550  // then use either a 32-bit loop or a 64-bit loop to search for
5551  // the Bcb.
5552  //
5553 
5554  if (FileOffset->HighPart == 0 &&
5555  Bcbt->NodeTypeCode == CACHE_NTC_BCB &&
5556  Bcbt->BeyondLastByte.HighPart == 0) {
5557 
5558  //
5559  // 32-bit - loop until we get back to a listhead.
5560  //
5561 
5562  while (Bcbt->NodeTypeCode == CACHE_NTC_BCB) {
5563 
5564  //
5565  // Since the Bcb list is in descending order, we first check
5566  // if we are completely beyond the current entry, and if so
5567  // get out.
5568  //
5569 
5570  if (FileOffset->LowPart >= Bcbt->BeyondLastByte.LowPart) {
5571  break;
5572  }
5573 
5574  //
5575  // Next check if the first byte we are looking for is
5576  // contained in the current Bcb. If so, we either have
5577  // a partial hit and must truncate to the exact amount
5578  // we have found, or we may have a complete hit. In
5579  // either case we break with Found == TRUE.
5580  //
5581 
5582  if (FileOffset->LowPart >= Bcbt->FileOffset.LowPart) {
5583  Found = TRUE;
5584  break;
5585  }
5586 
5587  //
5588  // Now we know we must loop back and keep looking, but we
5589  // still must check for the case where the tail end of the
5590  // bytes we are looking for are described by the current
5591  // Bcb. If so we must truncate what we are looking for,
5592  // because this routine is only supposed to return bytes
5593  // from the start of the desired range.
5594  //
5595 
5596  if (BeyondLastByte->LowPart >= Bcbt->FileOffset.LowPart) {
5597  BeyondLastByte->LowPart = Bcbt->FileOffset.LowPart;
5598  }
5599 
5600  //
5601  // Advance to next entry in list (which is possibly back to
5602  // the listhead) and loop back.
5603  //
5604 
5605  Bcbt = CONTAINING_RECORD( Bcbt->BcbLinks.Flink,
5606  BCB,
5607  BcbLinks );
5608 
5609  }
5610 
5611  } else {
5612 
5613  //
5614  // 64-bit - Loop until we get back to a listhead.
5615  //
5616 
5617  while (Bcbt->NodeTypeCode == CACHE_NTC_BCB) {
5618 
5619  //
5620  // Since the Bcb list is in descending order, we first check
5621  // if we are completely beyond the current entry, and if so
5622  // get out.
5623  //
5624 
5625  if (FileOffset->QuadPart >= Bcbt->BeyondLastByte.QuadPart) {
5626  break;
5627  }
5628 
5629  //
5630  // Next check if the first byte we are looking for is
5631  // contained in the current Bcb. If so, we either have
5632  // a partial hit and must truncate to the exact amount
5633  // we have found, or we may have a complete hit. In
5634  // either case we break with Found == TRUE.
5635  //
5636 
5637  if (FileOffset->QuadPart >= Bcbt->FileOffset.QuadPart) {
5638  Found = TRUE;
5639  break;
5640  }
5641 
5642  //
5643  // Now we know we must loop back and keep looking, but we
5644  // still must check for the case where the tail end of the
5645  // bytes we are looking for are described by the current
5646  // Bcb. If so we must truncate what we are looking for,
5647  // because this routine is only supposed to return bytes
5648  // from the start of the desired range.
5649  //
5650 
5651  if (BeyondLastByte->QuadPart >= Bcbt->FileOffset.QuadPart) {
5652  BeyondLastByte->QuadPart = Bcbt->FileOffset.QuadPart;
5653  }
5654 
5655  //
5656  // Advance to next entry in list (which is possibly back to
5657  // the listhead) and loop back.
5658  //
5659 
5660  Bcbt = CONTAINING_RECORD( Bcbt->BcbLinks.Flink,
5661  BCB,
5662  BcbLinks );
5663 
5664  }
5665  }
5666 
5667  *Bcb = Bcbt;
5668 
5669  DebugTrace2(0, me, " <TrialLength = %08lx, %08lx\n", TrialLength->LowPart,
5670  TrialLength->HighPart );
5671  DebugTrace( 0, me, " <Bcb = %08lx\n", *Bcb );
5672  DebugTrace(-1, me, "CcFindBcb -> %02lx\n", Found );
5673 
5674  return Found;
5675 }

5682 PBCB
5683 CcAllocateInitializeBcb (
5684  IN OUT PSHARED_CACHE_MAP SharedCacheMap OPTIONAL,
5685  IN OUT PBCB AfterBcb,
5686  IN PLARGE_INTEGER FileOffset,
5687  IN PLARGE_INTEGER TrialLength
5688  )
5689 
5690 /*++
5691 
5692 Routine Description:
5693 
5694  This routine allocates and initializes a Bcb to describe the specified
5695  byte range, and inserts it into the Bcb List of the specified Shared
5696  Cache Map. The Bcb List spin lock must currently be acquired.
5697 
5698  BcbSpinLock must be acquired on entry.
5699 
5700 Arguments:
5701 
5702  SharedCacheMap - Supplies the SharedCacheMap for the new Bcb.
5703 
5704  AfterBcb - Supplies where in the descending-order BcbList the new Bcb
5705  should be inserted: either the ListHead (masquerading as
5706  a Bcb) or a Bcb.
5707 
5708  FileOffset - Supplies File Offset for the desired data.
5709 
5710  TrialLength - Supplies length of desired data.
5711 
5712 Return Value:
5713 
5714  Address of the allocated and initialized Bcb
5715 
5716 --*/
5717 
5718 {
5719  PBCB Bcb;
5720  ULONG RoundedBcbSize = (sizeof(BCB) + 7) & ~7;
5721 
5722  if ((Bcb = ExAllocatePoolWithTag( NonPagedPool, sizeof(BCB), 'cBcC')) == NULL) {
5723 
5724  return NULL;
5725  }
5726 
5727  //
5728  // Initialize the newly allocated Bcb. First zero it, then fill in
5729  // nonzero fields.
5730  //
5731 
5732  RtlZeroMemory( Bcb, RoundedBcbSize );
5733 
5734  //
5735  // For Mbcb's, SharedCacheMap is NULL, and the rest of this initialization
5736  // is not desired.
5737  //
5738 
5739  if (SharedCacheMap != NULL) {
5740 
5741  Bcb->NodeTypeCode = CACHE_NTC_BCB;
5742  Bcb->FileOffset = *FileOffset;
5743  Bcb->ByteLength = TrialLength->LowPart;
5744  Bcb->BeyondLastByte.QuadPart = FileOffset->QuadPart + TrialLength->QuadPart;
5745  Bcb->PinCount += 1;
5746  ExInitializeResourceLite( &Bcb->Resource );
5747  Bcb->SharedCacheMap = SharedCacheMap;
5748 
5749  //
5750  // Since CcCalculateVacbLockCount has to be able to walk
5751  // the BcbList with only the VacbSpinLock, we take that one
5752  // out to change the list and set the count.
5753  //
5754 
5755  CcAcquireVacbLockAtDpcLevel();
5756  InsertTailList( &AfterBcb->BcbLinks, &Bcb->BcbLinks );
5757 
5758  ASSERT( (SharedCacheMap->SectionSize.QuadPart < VACB_SIZE_OF_FIRST_LEVEL) ||
5759  (CcFindBcb(SharedCacheMap, FileOffset, &Bcb->BeyondLastByte, &AfterBcb) &&
5760  (Bcb == AfterBcb)) );
5761 
5762  //
5763  // Now for large metadata streams we lock the Vacb level.
5764  //
5765 
5766  CcLockVacbLevel( SharedCacheMap, FileOffset->QuadPart );
5767  CcReleaseVacbLockFromDpcLevel();
5768 
5769  //
5770  // If this resource was no write behind, let Ex know that the
5771  // resource will never be acquired exclusive. Also disable boost.
5772  //
5773 
5774  if (SharedCacheMap &&
5775  FlagOn(SharedCacheMap->Flags, DISABLE_WRITE_BEHIND)) {
5776 #if DBG
5777  SetFlag(Bcb->Resource.Flag, ResourceNeverExclusive);
5778 #endif
5779  ExDisableResourceBoost( &Bcb->Resource );
5780  }
5781  }
5782 
5783  return Bcb;
5784 }

5898 
5899  ULONG PagesToGo;
5900 
5901  //
5902  // Now loop to touch all of the pages, calling MM to ensure
5903  // that if we fault, we take in exactly the number of pages
5904  // we need.
5905  //
5906 
5907  PagesToGo = ADDRESS_AND_SIZE_TO_SPAN_PAGES( BaseAddress, Length );
5908 
5909  //
5910  // Loop to touch or zero the pages.
5911  //
5912 
5913  ZeroCase = ZERO_FIRST_PAGE;
5914 
5915  while (PagesToGo) {
5916 
5917  //
5918  // If we cannot zero this page, or Mm failed to return
5919  // a zeroed page, then just fault it in.
5920  //
5921 
5922  MmSetPageFaultReadAhead( Thread, (PagesToGo - 1) );
5923 
5924  if (!FlagOn(ZeroFlags, ZeroCase) ||
5925  !MmCheckCachedPageState(BaseAddress, TRUE)) {
5926 
5927  //
5928  // If we get here, it is almost certainly due to the fact
5929  // that we can not take a zero page. MmCheckCachedPageState
5930  // will so rarely return FALSE, that we will not worry
5931  // about it. We will only check if the page is there if
5932  // Wait is FALSE, so that we can do the right thing.
5933  //
5934 
5935  if (!MmCheckCachedPageState(BaseAddress, FALSE) && !Wait) {
5936  try_return( Result = FALSE );
5937  }
5938  }
5939 
5940  BaseAddress = (PCHAR)BaseAddress + PAGE_SIZE;
5941  PagesToGo -= 1;
5942 
5943  if (PagesToGo == 1) {
5944  ZeroCase = ZERO_LAST_PAGE;
5945  } else {
5946  ZeroCase = ZERO_MIDDLE_PAGES;
5947  }
5948  }
5949 
5950  try_return( Result = TRUE );
5951 
5952  try_exit: NOTHING;
5953  }
5954 
5955  //
5956  // Cleanup on the way out.
5957  //
5958 
5959  finally {
5960 
5961  MmResetPageFaultReadAhead(Thread, SavedState);
5962  }
5963 
5964  return Result;
5965 }

5967 
5968 //
5969 // Internal Support Routine
5970 //
5971 
5972 VOID
5973 CcFreeActiveVacb (
5974  IN PSHARED_CACHE_MAP SharedCacheMap,
5975  IN PVACB ActiveVacb OPTIONAL,
5976  IN ULONG ActivePage,
5977  IN ULONG PageIsDirty
5978  )
5979 
5980 /*++
5981 
5982 Routine Description:
5983 
5984  This routine may be called to zero the end of a locked page or
5985  free the ActiveVacb for a Shared Cache Map, if there is one.
5986  Note that some callers are not synchronized with foreground
5987  activity, and may therefore not have an ActiveVacb. Examples
5988  of unsynchronized callers are CcZeroEndOfLastPage (which is
5989  called by MM) and any flushing done by CcWriteBehind.
5990 
5991 Arguments:
5992 
5993  SharedCacheMap - SharedCacheMap to examine for page to be zeroed.
5994 
5995  ActiveVacb - Vacb to free
5996 
5997  ActivePage - Page that was used
5998 
5999  PageIsDirty - ACTIVE_PAGE_IS_DIRTY if the active page is dirty
6000 
6001 Return Value:
6002 
6003  None
6004 
6005 --*/
6006 
6007 {
6008  LARGE_INTEGER ActiveOffset;
6009  PVOID ActiveAddress;
6010  ULONG BytesLeftInPage;
6011  KIRQL OldIrql;
6012 
6013  //
6014  // If the page was locked, then unlock it.
6015  //
6016 
6017  if (SharedCacheMap->NeedToZero != NULL) {
6018 
6019  PVACB NeedToZeroVacb;
6020 
6021  //
6022  // Zero the rest of the page under spinlock control,
6023  // and then clear the address field. This field makes
6024  // zero->nonzero transitions only when the file is exclusive,
6025  // but it can make nonzero->zero transitions any time the
6026  // spinlock is not held.
6027  //
6028 
6029  ExAcquireFastLock( &SharedCacheMap->ActiveVacbSpinLock, &OldIrql );
6030 
6031  //
6032  // The address could already be gone.
6033  //
6034 
6035  ActiveAddress = SharedCacheMap->NeedToZero;
6036  if (ActiveAddress != NULL) {
6037 
6038  BytesLeftInPage = PAGE_SIZE - ((((ULONG)((ULONG_PTR)ActiveAddress) - 1) & (PAGE_SIZE - 1)) + 1);
6039 
6040  RtlZeroBytes( ActiveAddress, BytesLeftInPage );
6041  NeedToZeroVacb = SharedCacheMap->NeedToZeroVacb;
6042  ASSERT( NeedToZeroVacb != NULL );
6043  SharedCacheMap->NeedToZero = NULL;
6044 
6045  }
6046  ExReleaseFastLock( &SharedCacheMap->ActiveVacbSpinLock, OldIrql );
6047 
6048  //
6049  // Now call MM to unlock the address. Note we will never store the
6050  // address at the start of the page, but we can sometimes store
6051  // the start of the next page when we have exactly filled the page.
6052  //
6053 
6054  if (ActiveAddress != NULL) {
6055  MmUnlockCachedPage( (PVOID)((PCHAR)ActiveAddress - 1) );
6056  CcFreeVirtualAddress( NeedToZeroVacb );
6057  }
6058  }
6059 
6060  //
6061  // See if caller actually has an ActiveVacb
6062  //
6063 
6064  if (ActiveVacb != NULL) {
6065 
6066  //
6067  // See if the page is dirty
6068  //
6069 
6070  if (PageIsDirty) {
6071 
6072  ActiveOffset.QuadPart = (LONGLONG)ActivePage << PAGE_SHIFT;
6073  ActiveAddress = (PVOID)((PCHAR)ActiveVacb->BaseAddress +
6074  (ActiveOffset.LowPart & (VACB_MAPPING_GRANULARITY - 1)));
6075 
6076  //
6077  // Tell the Lazy Writer to write the page.
6078  //
6079 
6080  CcSetDirtyInMask( SharedCacheMap, &ActiveOffset, PAGE_SIZE );
6081 
6082  //
6083  // Now we need to clear the flag and decrement some counts if there is
6084  // no other active Vacb which snuck in.
6085  //
6086 
6087  CcAcquireMasterLock( &OldIrql );
6088  ExAcquireSpinLockAtDpcLevel( &SharedCacheMap->ActiveVacbSpinLock );
6089  if ((SharedCacheMap->ActiveVacb == NULL) &&
6090  FlagOn(SharedCacheMap->Flags, ACTIVE_PAGE_IS_DIRTY)) {
6091 
6092  ClearFlag(SharedCacheMap->Flags, ACTIVE_PAGE_IS_DIRTY);
6093  CcDeductDirtyPages( SharedCacheMap, 1);
6094  }
6095  ExReleaseSpinLockFromDpcLevel( &SharedCacheMap->ActiveVacbSpinLock );
6096  CcReleaseMasterLock( OldIrql );
6097  }
6098 
6099  //
6100  // Now free the Vacb.
6101  //
6102 
6103  CcFreeVirtualAddress( ActiveVacb );
6104  }
6105 }

6108 //
6109 // Internal Support Routine
6110 //
6111 
6112 BOOLEAN
6113 CcMapAndCopy(
6114  IN PSHARED_CACHE_MAP SharedCacheMap,
6115  IN PVOID UserBuffer,
6116  IN PLARGE_INTEGER FileOffset,
6117  IN ULONG Length,
6118  IN ULONG OptimizeFlags,
6119  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
6120  IN PLARGE_INTEGER ValidDataLength,
6121  IN BOOLEAN Wait
6122  )
6123 
6124 /*++
6125 
6126 Routine Description:
6127 
6128  This routine may be called to copy the specified user data to the
6129  cache via a special Mm routine which copies the data to uninitialized
6130  pages and returns.
6131 
6132 Arguments:
6133 
6134  SharedCacheMap - Supplies the address of the SharedCacheMap for the
6135  data.
6136 
6137  UserBuffer - unsafe buffer supplying the user's data to be written
6138 
6139  FileOffset - Supplies the file offset to be modified
6140 
6141  Length - Supplies the total amount of data
6142 
6143  OptimizeFlags - Defines which pages can use the MmCopyToCachedPage
6144  optimization.
6145 
6146  FileObject - Supplies the file object being written to
6147 
6148  ValidDataLength - The file system's current record of this files valid
6149  data length. This is used to know if we can use a zero page when
6150  using the MmCopyToCachedPage optimization.
6151 
6152  Wait - FALSE if caller may not block, TRUE otherwise
6153 
6154 Return Value:
6155 
6156  FALSE - if the caller supplied Wait = FALSE and the data could not
6157  be returned without blocking.
6158 
6159  TRUE - if the data is being returned.
6160 
6161 --*/
6162 
6163 {
6164  ULONG ReceivedLength;
6165  ULONG OptimizeCase;
6166  PVOID CacheBuffer;
6167  PVOID SavedMappedBuffer;
6168  ULONG SavedMappedLength;
6169  ULONG ActivePage;
6170  KIRQL OldIrql;
6171  LARGE_INTEGER PFileOffset;
6172  IO_STATUS_BLOCK IoStatus;
6173  NTSTATUS Status;
6174  ULONG SavedState;
6175  LOGICAL MorePages;
6176  BOOLEAN WriteThrough = BooleanFlagOn( FileObject->Flags, FO_WRITE_THROUGH );
6177  ULONG SavedTotalLength = Length;
6178  LARGE_INTEGER LocalOffset;
6179  ULONG PageOffset = FileOffset->LowPart & (PAGE_SIZE - 1);
6180  PVACB Vacb = NULL;
6181  PETHREAD Thread = PsGetCurrentThread();
6182  BOOLEAN Result = FALSE;
6183 
6184  //
6185  // Initialize SavePage to TRUE to skip the finally clause on zero-length
6186  // writes.
6187  //
6188 
6189  BOOLEAN SavePage = TRUE;
6190 
6191  //
6192  // PREfix needs to see this explicitly, as opposed to a structure copy.
6193  //
6194 
6195  LocalOffset.QuadPart = FileOffset->QuadPart;
6196 
6197  DebugTrace(+1, me, "CcMapAndCopy:\n", 0 );
6198  DebugTrace( 0, me, " SharedCacheMap = %08lx\n", SharedCacheMap );
6199  DebugTrace2(0, me, " FileOffset = %08lx, %08lx\n", FileOffset->LowPart,
6200  FileOffset->HighPart );
6201  DebugTrace( 0, me, " Length = %08lx\n", Length );
6202 
6203  MmSavePageFaultReadAhead( Thread, &SavedState );
6204 
6205  //
6206  // See if we need to force write through. If the file object is of remote origin,
6207  // it has been exempted from throttling. As a result, it is possible that too
6208  // many pages will get dirty. In order to prevent this, we force write through
6209  // on these file objects if we would have throttled them in the first place.
6210  //
6211 
6212  if (!WriteThrough) {
6213 
6214  WriteThrough = CcForceWriteThrough( FileObject,
6215  Length,
6216  SharedCacheMap,
6217  TRUE );
6218  }
6219 
6220  //
6221  // If this is a WriteThrough operation, return FALSE here if the caller
6222  // cannot block since the flushes necessary for WriteThrough will be
6223  // synchronous. This will more accurately honor the Wait == FALSE request.
6224  //
6225 
6226  if (WriteThrough && !Wait) {
6227 
6228  return FALSE;
6229  }
6230 
6231  //
6232  // try around everything for cleanup.
6233  //
6234 
6235  try {
6236 
6237  while (Length != 0) {
6238 
6239  SavedMappedLength = 0;
6240  CacheBuffer = CcGetVirtualAddress( SharedCacheMap,
6241  LocalOffset,
6242  &Vacb,
6243  &ReceivedLength );
6244 
6245  //
6246  // PREfix wants to know this cannot be NULL, otherwise it
6247  // will complain.
6248  //
6249 
6250  ASSERT( CacheBuffer != NULL );
6251 
6252  //
6253  // If we got more than we need, make sure to only use
6254  // the right amount.
6255  //
6256 
6257  if (ReceivedLength > Length) {
6258  ReceivedLength = Length;
6259  }
6260  SavedMappedBuffer = CacheBuffer;
6261  SavedMappedLength = ReceivedLength;
6262  Length -= ReceivedLength;
6263 
6264  //
6265  // Now loop to touch all of the pages, calling MM to ensure
6266  // that if we fault, we take in exactly the number of pages
6267  // we need.
6268  //
6269 
6270  CacheBuffer = (PVOID)((PCHAR)CacheBuffer - PageOffset);
6271  ReceivedLength += PageOffset;
6272 
6273  //
6274  // Loop to touch or zero the pages.
6275  //
6276 
6277  OptimizeCase = OPTIMIZE_FIRST_PAGE;
6278 
6279  //
6280  // Set up offset to page for use below.
6281  //
6282 
6283  PFileOffset = LocalOffset;
6284  PFileOffset.LowPart -= PageOffset;
6285 
6286  while (TRUE) {
6287 
6288  //
6289  // Calculate whether we wish to save an active page
6290  // or not.
6291  //
6292 
6293  SavePage = (BOOLEAN) ((Length == 0) &&
6294  (ReceivedLength < PAGE_SIZE) &&
6295  (SavedTotalLength <= (PAGE_SIZE / 2)) &&
6296  !WriteThrough);
6297 
6298  MorePages = (ReceivedLength > PAGE_SIZE);
6299 
6300  //
6301  // Copy the data to the user buffer.
6302  //
6303 
6304  //
6305  // It is possible that there is a locked page
6306  // hanging around, and so we need to delete it here.
6307  //
6308 
6309  if (SharedCacheMap->NeedToZero != NULL) {
6310  CcFreeActiveVacb( SharedCacheMap, NULL, 0, 0 );
6311  }
6312 
6313  Status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
6314  if (FlagOn(OptimizeFlags, OptimizeCase)) {
6315 
6316  Status = MmCopyToCachedPage( CacheBuffer,
6317  UserBuffer,
6318  PageOffset,
6319  MorePages ?
6320  (PAGE_SIZE - PageOffset) :
6321  (ReceivedLength - PageOffset),
6322  (PFileOffset.QuadPart >= ValidDataLength->QuadPart) ?
6323  TRUE :
6324  FALSE );
6325 
6326  if (!NT_SUCCESS (Status)) {
6327 
6328  //
6329  // We got some error -- this indicates that
6330  // the user buffer was invalid, so we will raise
6331  // here.
6332  //
6333 
6334  ExRaiseStatus( FsRtlNormalizeNtstatus( Status,
6335  STATUS_INVALID_USER_BUFFER ));
6336  }
6337 
6338  //
6339  // Otherwise, we have to actually copy the data ourselves after
6340  // checking whether or not the page is resident.
6341  //
6342 
6343  } else {
6344 
6345  MmSetPageFaultReadAhead( Thread,
6346  (MorePages && FlagOn(OptimizeFlags, OPTIMIZE_LAST_PAGE)) ? 1 : 0);
6347 
6348  if (!MmCheckCachedPageState(CacheBuffer, FALSE) && !Wait) {
6349 
6350  //
6351  // The page is not resident and the caller does not
6352  // want to wait, so we will just return here.
6353  //
6354 
6355  try_return( Result = FALSE );
6356 
6357  } else {
6358 
6359  try {
6360 
6361  RtlCopyBytes( (PVOID)((PCHAR)CacheBuffer + PageOffset),
6362  UserBuffer,
6363  MorePages ?
6364  (PAGE_SIZE - PageOffset) :
6365  (ReceivedLength - PageOffset) );
6366 
6367  } except( CcCopyReadExceptionFilter( GetExceptionInformation(),
6368  &Status ) ) {
6369 
6370  //
6371  // If we got an access violation, then the user buffer went
6372  // away. Otherwise we must have gotten an I/O error trying
6373  // to bring the data in.
6374  //
6375 
6376  if (Status == STATUS_ACCESS_VIOLATION) {
6377  ExRaiseStatus( STATUS_INVALID_USER_BUFFER );
6378  }
6379  else {
6380  ExRaiseStatus( FsRtlNormalizeNtstatus( Status,
6381  STATUS_UNEXPECTED_IO_ERROR ));
6382  }
6383  }
6384  }
6385 
6386  MmResetPageFaultReadAhead( Thread, SavedState );
6387  }
6388 
6389  //
6390  // Now get out quickly if it is a small write and we want
6391  // to save the page.
6392  //
6393 
6394  if (SavePage) {
6395 
6396  ActivePage = (ULONG)( Vacb->Overlay.FileOffset.QuadPart >> PAGE_SHIFT ) +
6397  (ULONG)(((PCHAR)CacheBuffer - (PCHAR)Vacb->BaseAddress) >>
6398  PAGE_SHIFT);
6399 
6400  PFileOffset.LowPart += ReceivedLength;
6401 
6402  SetActiveVacb( SharedCacheMap,
6403  OldIrql,
6404  Vacb,
6405  ActivePage,
6406  ACTIVE_PAGE_IS_DIRTY );
6407 
6408  //
6409  // Must set the VACB to NULL here because we do not want to
6410  // unmap it below.
6411  //
6412 
6413  Vacb = NULL;
6414 
6415  try_return( Result = TRUE );
6416  }
6417 
6418  //
6419  // If it looks like we may save a page and exit on the next loop,
6420  // then we must make sure to mark the current page dirty. Note
6421  // that Cc[Fast]CopyWrite will finish the last part of any page
6422  // before allowing us to free the Active Vacb above, therefore
6423  // this case only occurs for a small random write.
6424  //
6425 
6426  if ((SavedTotalLength <= (PAGE_SIZE / 2)) && !WriteThrough) {
6427 
6428  CcSetDirtyInMask( SharedCacheMap, &PFileOffset, ReceivedLength );
6429  }
6430 
6431  UserBuffer = (PVOID)((PCHAR)UserBuffer + (PAGE_SIZE - PageOffset));
6432  PageOffset = 0;
6433 
6434  //
6435  // If there is more than a page to go (including what we just
6436  // copied), then adjust our buffer pointer and counts, and
6437  // determine if we are to the last page yet.
6438  //
6439 
6440  if (MorePages) {
6441 
6442  CacheBuffer = (PCHAR)CacheBuffer + PAGE_SIZE;
6443  ReceivedLength -= PAGE_SIZE;
6444 
6445  //
6446  // Update our offset to the page. Note that 32-bit
6447  // add is ok since we cannot cross a Vacb boundary
6448  // and we reinitialize this offset before entering
6449  // this loop again.
6450  //
6451 
6452  PFileOffset.LowPart += PAGE_SIZE;
6453 
6454  //
6455  // Update what region of the file we are currently working
6456  // on.
6457  //
6458 
6459  if (ReceivedLength > PAGE_SIZE) {
6460  OptimizeCase = OPTIMIZE_MIDDLE_PAGES;
6461  } else {
6462  OptimizeCase = OPTIMIZE_LAST_PAGE;
6463  }
6464 
6465  } else {
6466 
6467  break;
6468  }
6469  }
6470 
6471  //
6472  // If there is still more to write (ie. we are going to step
6473  // onto the next vacb) AND we just dirtied more than 64K, then
6474  // do a vicarious MmFlushSection here. This prevents us from
6475  // creating unlimited dirty pages while holding the file
6476  // resource exclusive. We also do not need to set the pages
6477  // dirty in the mask in this case.
6478  //
6479 
6480  if (Length > CcMaxDirtyWrite) {
6481 
6482  MmSetAddressRangeModified( SavedMappedBuffer, SavedMappedLength );
6483  MmFlushSection( SharedCacheMap->FileObject->SectionObjectPointer,
6484  &LocalOffset,
6485  SavedMappedLength,
6486  &IoStatus,
6487  MM_FLUSH_ACQUIRE_FILE );
6488 
6489  ASSERT( IoStatus.Status != STATUS_ENCOUNTERED_WRITE_IN_PROGRESS );
6490 
6491  if (!NT_SUCCESS(IoStatus.Status)) {
6492  ExRaiseStatus( FsRtlNormalizeNtstatus( IoStatus.Status,
6493  STATUS_UNEXPECTED_IO_ERROR ));
6494  }
6495 
6496  //
6497  // For write through files, call Mm to propagate the dirty bits
6498  // here while we have the view mapped, so we know the flush will
6499  // work below. Again - do not set dirty in the mask.
6500  //
6501 
6502  } else if (WriteThrough) {
6503 
6504  MmSetAddressRangeModified( SavedMappedBuffer, SavedMappedLength );
6505 
6506  //
6507  // For the normal case, just set the pages dirty for the Lazy Writer
6508  // now.
6509  //
6510 
6511  } else {
6512 
6513  CcSetDirtyInMask( SharedCacheMap, &LocalOffset, SavedMappedLength );
6514  }
6515 
6516  CcFreeVirtualAddress( Vacb );
6517  Vacb = NULL;
6518 
6519  //
6520  // If we have to loop back to get at least a page, it will be ok to
6521  // try to optimize our write to the first page. If we are not
6522  // getting at least a page, we must make sure we clear the
6523  // OptimizeFlags if we cannot optimize the last page.
6524  //
6525 
6526  if (Length >= PAGE_SIZE) {
6527  OptimizeFlags |= OPTIMIZE_FIRST_PAGE;
6528  } else if (!FlagOn( OptimizeFlags, OPTIMIZE_LAST_PAGE )) {
6529  OptimizeFlags = 0;
6530  }
6531 
6532  //
6533  // Note that if ReceivedLength (and therefore SavedMappedLength)
6534  // was truncated to the transfer size then the new LocalOffset
6535  // computed below is not correct. This is not an issue since
6536  // in that case (Length == 0) and we would never get here.
6537  //
6538 
6539  LocalOffset.QuadPart = LocalOffset.QuadPart + (LONGLONG)SavedMappedLength;
6540  }
6541 
6542  try_return( Result = TRUE );
6543 
6544  try_exit: NOTHING;
6545  }
6546 
6547  //
6548  // Cleanup on the way out.
6549  //
6550 
6551  finally {
6552 
6553  MmResetPageFaultReadAhead( Thread, SavedState );
6554 
6555  //
6556  // Make sure that we do not leave the Vacb mapped if it is non-null.
6557  //
6558 
6559  if (Vacb != NULL) {
6560 
6561  CcFreeVirtualAddress( Vacb );
6562  }
6563 
6564  //
6565  // We have no work to do if we have squirreled away the Vacb.
6566  //
6567 
6568  if (!SavePage || AbnormalTermination()) {
6569 
6570  //
6571  // If this is write through, flush the whole range.
6572  //
6573 
6574  if (WriteThrough) {
6575 
6576  if (AbnormalTermination() && (0 != SavedMappedLength)) {
6577 
6578  //
6579  // If we have hit an exception, we need to assume that all
6580  // the pages we were currently working on were modified.
6581  // Mark them as such so they will get flushed.
6582  //
6583 
6584  MmSetAddressRangeModified( SavedMappedBuffer, SavedMappedLength );
6585  }
6586 
6587  MmFlushSection ( SharedCacheMap->FileObject->SectionObjectPointer,
6588  FileOffset,
6589  SavedTotalLength,
6590  &IoStatus,
6591  MM_FLUSH_ACQUIRE_FILE );
6592 
6593  ASSERT( IoStatus.Status != STATUS_ENCOUNTERED_WRITE_IN_PROGRESS );
6594 
6595  //
6596  // If we successfully flushed the file, move forward
6597  // ValidDataGoal. Otherwise, if we get an error we will
6598  // raise the error only if we are not already handling an
6599  // exception. If we raised again, we would get into an endless
6600  // recursive loop of executing this finally handler.
6601  //
6602 
6603  if (NT_SUCCESS( IoStatus.Status )) {
6604 
6605  //
6606  // Advance ValidDataGoal if we successfully flushed.
6607  //
6608 
6609  LocalOffset.QuadPart = FileOffset->QuadPart + (LONGLONG)SavedTotalLength;
6610  if (LocalOffset.QuadPart > SharedCacheMap->ValidDataGoal.QuadPart) {
6611  SharedCacheMap->ValidDataGoal = LocalOffset;
6612  }
6613 
6614  } else {
6615 
6616  if (!AbnormalTermination()) {
6617 
6618  ExRaiseStatus( FsRtlNormalizeNtstatus( IoStatus.Status,
6619  STATUS_UNEXPECTED_IO_ERROR ));
6620  }
6621  }
6622  }
6623  else if (AbnormalTermination() && (0 != SavedMappedLength)) {
6624 
6625  //
6626  // If we have hit an exception, we need to mark the last
6627  // range we were working on as dirty. Any range we successfully
6628  // copied will have already been marked dirty.
6629  //
6630 
6631  CcSetDirtyInMask( SharedCacheMap, &LocalOffset, SavedMappedLength );
6632  }
6633  }
6634  }
6635 
6636  DebugTrace(-1, me, "CcMapAndCopy -> %02lx\n", Result );
6637 
6638  return Result;
6639 }

6642 BOOLEAN
6643 CcLogError(
6644  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
6645  IN PUNICODE_STRING FileName,
6646  IN NTSTATUS Error,
6647  IN NTSTATUS DeviceError,
6648  IN UCHAR IrpMajorCode
6649  )
6650 
6651 /*++
6652 
6653 Routine Description:
6654 
6655  This routine writes an eventlog entry to the eventlog.
6656 
6657 Arguments:
6658 
6659  FileObject - The fileobject in whose context the error occured.
6660 
6661  FileName - The filename to use in logging the error (usually the DOS-side name)
6662 
6663  Error - The error to log in the eventlog record
6664 
6665  DeviceError - The actual error that occured in the device - will be logged
6666  as user data
6667 
6668 Return Value:
6669 
6670  True if successful, false if internal memory allocation failed
6671 
6672 --*/
6673 
6674 {
6675  UCHAR ErrorPacketLength;
6676  UCHAR BasePacketLength;
6677  ULONG StringLength;
6678  PIO_ERROR_LOG_PACKET ErrorLogEntry = NULL;
6679  BOOLEAN Result = FALSE;
6680  PWCHAR String;
6681 
6682  PAGED_CODE();
6683 
6684  //
6685  // Get our error packet, holding the string and status code. Note we log against the
6686  // true filesystem if this is available.
6687  //
6688  // The sizing of the packet is a bit slimy since the dumpdata is already grown by a
6689  // ULONG onto the end of the packet. Since NTSTATUS is ULONG, well, we just work in
6690  // place.
6691  //
6692 
6693  BasePacketLength = sizeof(IO_ERROR_LOG_PACKET);
6694  if ((BasePacketLength + FileName->Length + sizeof(WCHAR)) <= ERROR_LOG_MAXIMUM_SIZE) {
6695  ErrorPacketLength = (UCHAR)(BasePacketLength + FileName->Length + sizeof(WCHAR));
6696  } else {
6697  ErrorPacketLength = ERROR_LOG_MAXIMUM_SIZE;
6698  }
6699 
6700  ErrorLogEntry = (PIO_ERROR_LOG_PACKET) IoAllocateErrorLogEntry( (FileObject->Vpb ?
6701  FileObject->Vpb->DeviceObject :
6702  FileObject->DeviceObject),
6703  ErrorPacketLength );
6704  if (ErrorLogEntry) {
6705 
6706  //
6707  // Fill in the nonzero members of the packet.
6708  //
6709 
6710  ErrorLogEntry->MajorFunctionCode = IrpMajorCode;
6711  ErrorLogEntry->ErrorCode = Error;
6712  ErrorLogEntry->FinalStatus = DeviceError;
6713 
6714  ErrorLogEntry->DumpDataSize = sizeof(NTSTATUS);
6715  RtlCopyMemory( &ErrorLogEntry->DumpData, &DeviceError, sizeof(NTSTATUS) );
6716 
6717  //
6718  // The filename string is appended to the end of the error log entry. We may
6719  // have to smash the middle to fit it in the limited space.
6720  //
6721 
6722  StringLength = ErrorPacketLength - BasePacketLength - sizeof(WCHAR);
6723 
6724  ASSERT(!(StringLength % sizeof(WCHAR)));
6725 
6726  String = (PWCHAR) ((PUCHAR)ErrorLogEntry + BasePacketLength);
6727  ErrorLogEntry->NumberOfStrings = 1;
6728  ErrorLogEntry->StringOffset = BasePacketLength;
6729 
6730  //
6731  // If the name does not fit in the packet, divide the name equally to the
6732  // prefix and suffix, with an ellipsis " .. " (4 wide characters) to indicate
6733  // the loss.
6734  //
6735 
6736  if (StringLength < FileName->Length) {
6737 
6738  //
6739  // Remember, prefix + " .. " + suffix is the length. Calculate by figuring
6740  // the prefix and then get the suffix by whacking the ellipsis and prefix off
6741  // the total.
6742  //
6743 
6744  ULONG NamePrefixSegmentLength = ((StringLength/sizeof(WCHAR))/2 - 2)*sizeof(WCHAR);
6745  ULONG NameSuffixSegmentLength = StringLength - 4*sizeof(WCHAR) - NamePrefixSegmentLength;
6746 
6747  ASSERT(!(NamePrefixSegmentLength % sizeof(WCHAR)));
6748  ASSERT(!(NameSuffixSegmentLength % sizeof(WCHAR)));
6749 
6750  RtlCopyMemory( String,
6751  FileName->Buffer,
6752  NamePrefixSegmentLength );
6753  String = (PWCHAR)((PCHAR)String + NamePrefixSegmentLength);
6754 
6755  RtlCopyMemory( String,
6756  L" .. ",
6757  4*sizeof(WCHAR) );
6758  String += 4;
6759 
6760  RtlCopyMemory( String,
6761  (PUCHAR)FileName->Buffer +
6762  FileName->Length - NameSuffixSegmentLength,
6763  NameSuffixSegmentLength );
6764  String = (PWCHAR)((PCHAR)String + NameSuffixSegmentLength);
6765 
6766  } else {
6767 
6768  RtlCopyMemory( String,
6769  FileName->Buffer,
6770  FileName->Length );
6771  String += FileName->Length/sizeof(WCHAR);
6772  }
6773 
6774  //
6775  // Null terminate the string and send the packet.
6776  //
6777 
6778  *String = L'\0';
6779 
6780  IoWriteErrorLogEntry( ErrorLogEntry );
6781  Result = TRUE;
6782  }
6783 
6784  return Result;
6785 }
